<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle     03-03 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Managers To Set Discovery Launch Date</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Late afternoon announcement expected.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Launch of the Discovery and its
five-astronaut crew could be scheduled for late next week as NASA
prepares for the third post-Challenger shuttle mission.
   NASA officials, who planned to announce a launch date today, said
Wednesday the liftoff would occur no sooner than March 11 because of
the need to replace a failed electrical part in one of the shuttle's
three main engines.
   The target date had been March 9, but the Air Force told NASA
Monday that it planned to launch a high-priority military rocket on
that day and could not support a shuttle flight with Air Force
tracking facilities.
   The electrical part problem apparently took care of that
potential conflict. But a delay in the military flight could affect
the shuttle launch on a day-by-day basis. The Air Force mission has
priority for national security reasons.
   During five days in orbit, Discovery's astronauts are to deploy a
large communications satellite and conduct scientific experiments.
</TEXT>
