<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0145EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Networks-Sweep     03-03 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Networks-Sweep,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC, CBS Rebound from Strike; ABC Still Struggling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The so-called February ratings sweep indicate NBC
and CBS have rebounded from last year's writers' strike, but network
executives say the September-April ``season'' used to track the
ratings race should be yearlong.
   ``I know you guys love races,'' said David Poltrack, CBS vice
president for marketing, ``but any discussion of full-season results
is a historical curiosity and not a marketing issue, and a
disservice to us.''
   Alan Wurtzel, ABC's senior vice president for marketing and
research, said the season race is now ``a spectator sport'' and
means nothing except for bragging rights.
   ``In 1989, to say there is a `season' is so antiquated,'' said
Wurtzel. ``That means we would be abdicating the audience five
months of the year, and that's not something we can afford to do.''
   NBC Entertainment President Brandon Tartikoff has long held that
the ratings race season should be year-round, too, but such talk
didn't come up at Thursday's NBC briefing on the February sweep
rating period _ one of four months a year when local TV ratings are
measured to determine advertising rates.
   But then, NBC is winning another season hands-down.
   Ten years ago when the average viewer had few channels available,
the networks didn't have to worry about losing their audience to
competition from cable or videocassettes over the summer, but times
have changed. The audience that has access to an average of 25
channels will go elsewhere if the networks fail to offer them what
they want to watch.
   In February, the networks did.
   The CBS miniseries ``Lonesome Dove'' and the heated competition
it encouraged boosted the networks' aggregate rating after a more
than yearlong decline.
   The four-night ``Lonesome Dove'' boosted third-place CBS above
ABC in the February sweep and makes second place for the season a
tossup.
   NBC won the sweep with an average A.C. Nielsen Co. rating of
16.3. CBS had a 14.7 and ABC a 12.4. The rating is a percentage of
90.4 million U.S. homes with televisions.
   ABC had a 28 percent decline in February compared to February
1988, when it had the Winter Olympics. NBC and CBS showed increases
this February over last.
   ABC was forced, because of the writers' strike, to run the first
18-hour stretch of its 32-hour miniseries ``War and Remembrance'' in
November. Hardly a ratings blockbuster, it still did better than
ABC's regular programming. The decision to run the program then came
back to haunt the network in February when ``War and Remembrance''
was to have run.
   ``Clearly we had a disappointing sweeps,'' said Wurtzel.
   ``We did not have an enormous inventory, because we had to play
`War and Remembrance' early, and we had planned to play it in
February,'' he said. ``The other two networks knew that and planned
accordingly.''
   CBS got a big push, both in ratings and morale, from the
critically acclaimed ``Lonesome Dove,'' the highest-rated network
miniseries in more than four years. But the miniseries' success
pleased ABC and NBC, too.
   ``I think `Lonesome Dove' was beneficial to everybody,'' said
Wurtzel. ``Network television needs to have exciting, well-made
programming.''
   NBC even used figures from the week of ``Lonesome Dove'' to
contend that network ``reach'' has not declined in the past decade,
even if ratings have.
   ``Say we (the networks) are all throwing a party,'' explained
Gerald Jaffe, NBC's vice president for research projects. ``The same
number of people come to the party, but instead of staying 2{ hours,
maybe they stay two hours, then they go to someone else's party.''
</TEXT>
