<FIRST>r a PM-DynamiteWine     03-03 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dynamite Wine,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beirut Vintner Dodges Bombs To Make Great Wine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winemaker Serge Hochar, like some of his
competitors, likes to sell no wine before its time. But in war-torn
Beirut, it's not always up to him to decide.
   ``You never know if you'll be hit,'' Hochar said Wednesday,
adding that he's missed some vintages when fighting broke out near
his Chateau Musar, the best-known of Lebanon's five wineries.
   ``I must say, I have been very lucky,'' said the vintner, whose
products are internationally rated among the top wines of the Middle
East. ``My home, 200 yards from the fire line between east and west
Beirut, has been bombed only three times in the last 14 years, and I
managed to escape.''
   The Beirut-born winemaker, who is in his 50s, styles his wine for
cosmopolitan tastes. He was in San Francisco on Wednesday on a
seven-city U.S. tour to market his wines, which ranged from 1959 to
1980.
   Despite his unpredictable environment, Hochar says he will not
release a vintage if he doesn't like it, and he insists on holding
his wines in cellars for at least eight years.
   ``I am not a political man. I am a wine man, and a wine man is a
human person because I work with life. I keep my vines and my wines
alive,'' he said.
   Hochar makes 15,000 to 20,000 cases of wine a year at the
30-year-old winery founded by his father, Gaston. The star is his
Bordeaux red, a blend of cabernet sauvignon, cinsault and syrah.
   It can take weeks for Hochar to get grapes from the Bekaa Valley,
40 miles south of Beirut, to his winery in Lebanon's embattled
capital city.
   ``We have to cross five or six checkpoints, many borders ...
sometimes we have to go south from the vineyard and sail back by
boat.''
   And everywhere, he said, he must pay duty, at each border and to
whomever has the power _ or a gun.
   ``You get used to it after a while,'' he said. ``You don't
realize you are in a war situation. You live with it. ... In
Lebanon, you can always manage to find a few friends to make things
easier.''
</TEXT>
