<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Labor     03-03 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Labor,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor and Business Await Bush Decision on Airline Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision on whether to
intervene in the threatened Eastern Airlines strike will show
whether he wants to improve relations with organized labor, a union
president says.
   Vincent Sombrotto, head of the National Association of Letter
Carriers, said that if Bush appoints an emergency investigative
board and delays the strike by 60 days, ``that would show a
recognition of American labor as an institution.''
   But if Bush refuses to invoke the law, Sombrotto said, ``that
would just be consistent with the Reagan administration's
laissez-faire attitude.''
   Former President Reagan responded to his first labor-management
crisis in August 1981 by firing some 11,400 striking air traffic
controllers, and Reagan's relations with organized labor suffered
throughout two terms.
   Now, the specter of a strike at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday has
forced Bush to decide whether he wants to invoke provisions of the
Railway Labor Act to impose a 60-day cooling off period.
   Alfred Kahn, who headed the now-defunct Civil Aeronautics Board
and was chairman of the Council on Wage and Price Stability during
the Carter administration, said it would be a mistake to intervene.
   But Audrey Freeman, an analyst with the private Conference Board
in New York, said she doubted that Bush's decision either way would
make a major statement about his intentions toward labor.
   ``I don't think the controllers strike changed the course of
history of labor-management relations,'' she said, ``and I don't
think that whatever Mr. Bush will do will change the course of labor
relations.''
   At midnight, the end of a 30-day cooling-off period set by the
National Mediation Board, Eastern can impose work conditions and the
union can strike. The board recommended that Bush name the emergency
panel.
   Kahn, who was instrumental in the late 1970s move to ease
government regulation of the airline industry and increase
competition, said, ``I think that if the Bush administration
succumbs, and appoints this board ... it would be tipping the scales
in favor of labor. It would be such a labor-dictated intervention it
could be seen as killing Eastern.''
   Kahn, in a telephone interview from the campus of New York
University, said ``the more they (the unions) can delay either a
strike or the probability of a settlement, the more they can
increase the chances of Eastern going under.''
   Mark de Bernardo, special counsel to the U.S. Chamber of
Commerce, said the union movement is ``going to unduly pressure the
new administration ... by raising the stakes'' in situations such as
the Eastern dispute.
   ``It's a fairly dangerous gambit, forcing this into an early
bellwether of where the Bush administration is going to go'' in the
area of labor-relations, he said. ``Government intervention was not
a hallmark of the Reagan administration.
   ``If he (Bush) makes the decision to intervene, it will be a
reluctant one,'' de Bernardo said.
   Sombrotto acknowledged that ``it's a little unusual'' for
organized labor to urge government intervention to stop a strike _
which is the ultimate weapon of unionized workers. But he said that
``it is a little different period.'' He said a strike would be
detrimental to ``the flying public'' and to the economy, as well as
to the Eastern Airlines employees.
   In contrast to earlier years, when the organized labor movement
was much stronger, the AFL-CIO has urged Bush to use this law to
delay a strike. In days past, government intervention to stop a
strike would have infuriated labor leaders. At the same time, Frank
Lorenzo, the chairman of Texas Air Corp., which owns Eastern, has
warned that putting off planned cuts in costs could send the carrier
to ``the corporate graveyard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
