<FIRST>r w PM-LandsatShutdown     03-03 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Landsat Shutdown,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Crunch Threatens to Pull Plug on Satellites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The future looks cloudy for the Landsat
satellites that keep on eye on the earth and its climate, with
shutdown likely by the end of the month unless more money can be
found.
   Congress only provided enough money to run the system through the
end of March and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
doesn't have any extra funds to keep them going, NOAA satellite
director Thomas N. Pyke Jr., said Thursday.
   As a result, the contractor that runs the satellites for the
government has been directed to begin shutting them down, Pyke said
in a telephone interview.
   A Landsat satellite scheduled for launch in 1991 is not affected.
   But Sen. Al Gore Jr., D-Tenn., blamed the decision on the
administration and called the funding halt ``one of the most
ridiculous policy decisions I have seen in 13 years of service in
the House and Senate.''
   ``At a time when we are trying to get more information about
environmental change, the Bush administration is shutting down one
of our best sources of information,'' said Gore, chairman of the
Commerce, Science and Transportation subcommittee on Science,
Technology and Space.
   All Landsat services, including access to more than 2 million
archive images of the planet, will cease March 15, the Earth
Observation Satellite Company (EOSAT) announced.
   ``If this is carried to completion, near the end of this month
they will actually pull the switch on these two satellites and place
them on internal control,'' Pyke said. ``Once that has been done it
may not be possible to reestablish communications with these
satellites.''
   In the meantime, however, the House Science, Space and Technology
Committee has called a hearing for next Tuesday to look into ways of
saving the satellite system.
   ``It makes absolutely no sense'' to shut down the satellites,
said Rep. George Brown, D-Calif., a committee member. He called on
President Bush to intercede immediately by asking the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration and the departments of Defense
and Agriculture to help fund the program.
   EOSAT Vice President Peter M. P. Norris termed the threatened
shutdown ``beyond belief.''
   ``The Landsat program provides important environmental data that
touches on projects throughout the world,'' Norris said.
   But, explained Pyke: ``We have gone to the other federal agencies
who make use of Landsat data and asked them if they can help with
the continued funding of Landsat operations, but as of today we have
received no additional funds from any source.''
   Currently, EOSAT operates two satellites, Landsats 4 and 5, which
provide photos used for a variety of purposes including mineral
exploration, checking soil conditions and vegetation, urban and
rural planning, monitoring volcanoes, tracing ocean currents and so
forth.
   Both satellites are well past their expected lifetimes and are
not fully operational, Pyke noted, but they are still providing
useful information.
   An improved satellite, Landsat 6, is under construction, Pyke
added. That project will continue because funds were provided to
complete and launch that satellite, which is expected to go into
service in 1991.
   EOSAT was established to take over Landsat operations in 1985
after the Reagan Administration sought to sell both Landsat and the
nation's weather satellites to commercial operators.
   Congress refused to approve sale of the weather satellites, but
permitted the Landsat sale, with federal support to be phased out
over five years.
   EOSAT has struggled financially in recent years, facing strong
competition from the French SPOT-Image satellite system and also the
possibility of civilian sales of satellite images by the Soviet
Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls     03-03 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bailout Cost Could Be Higher than Bush Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost to taxpayers of President Bush's
savings and loan plan could jump by more than a third if the
administration's economic assumptions turn out to be too optimistic,
the White House budget director says.
   Richard Darman, director of the Office of Management and Budget,
acknowledged on Thursday that economic projections showing interest
rates declining by 5 percentage points over the next five years are
optimistic
   But the administration's plan to close and sell off insolvent
savings institutions has a $10 billion to $15 billion ``fudge
factor'' that should accommodate any increase in costs caused by
higher interest rates, he told the Senate Banking Committee.
   Darman said if interest rates stay on average 2 percentage points
above what the administration projects, budget outlays for the S&amp;L
plan from 1989 through 1999 would rise from $39.9 billion to $50.6
billion.
   And if deposits at S&amp;Ls grow at a 4 percent annual rate instead
of the 7 percent forecast, budget outlays would swell by another
$4.7 billion to make up for a lower level of deposit insurance
premiums, he said.
   Darman vigorously defended Bush's proposal to borrow S&amp;L rescue
money in a way that keeps $50 billion in spending out of the budget
deficit.
   Darman said adding $50 billion to the deficit would risk a larger
crisis while Congress and the administration tried to agree on how
to meet the targets of the Gramm-Rudman law.
   ``I think it could well bring the political system to
stalemate,'' he said. ``The net effect of that would be to drive
interest rates up higher (and) force us into recession.''
   In other S&amp;L developments:
   _The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. took control of 37 more
insolvent S&amp;Ls, bringing the total under its supervision to 73. The
37 were in six states: 12 in Texas, 10 in Kansas, eight in Arkansas,
four in Louisiana, two in Alaska and one in Maryland.
   Although the FDIC regulates commercial banks, it is taking over
the 220 worst-off S&amp;Ls in preparation for the regulatory
reorganization proposed by Bush.
   _Former Democratic presidential candidate Jesse Jackson and Rep.
Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas, chairman of the House Banking Committee,
backed a liberal coalition's proposal to require financial
institutions to commit money to low-and moderate-income housing as a
concession for an S&amp;L bailout.
   The coalition would finance its proposal by boosting the top
federal income tax rate from 33 percent to 38 percent and by making
assessments on brokerage firms and mutual funds, as well as banks
and S&amp;Ls.
   _Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady won the support of a major
banking group for the administration S&amp;L plan. The board of the
American Bankers Association voted unanimously to work for the plan
even though it would nearly double deposit insurance premiums paid
by banks.
   The ABA's support was conditioned on the eventual granting of
partial premium rebates and on capping the premium at 15 cents per
$100 of deposits. The administration proposal would permit
regulators, if necessary, to raise the premium as high as 35 cents.
   _The General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative agency,
told a House panel that ``junk bonds'' have been a profitable
investment for S&amp;Ls, but warned that their safety hasn't been tested
during an economic downturn.
   The GAO told the House Banking subcommittee that the nation's
S&amp;Ls, had invested about $13 billion in junk bonds as of Sept. 30.
The bonds pay higher interest but carry a greater risk of default.
   On another point, Darman said the administration is forecasting
that 200 of the nation's 2,950 S&amp;Ls will fail because they will be
unable to meet stricter capital standards requiring S&amp;L owners to
put up more of their own money within two years. That's in addition
to the 350 that have already failed and are awaiting closure.
</TEXT>
