<FIRST>r w PM-Greenspan     03-03 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greenspan,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fed Chief Says Money Moves Have Kept Inflation at Bay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan insists
that the Fed's anti-inflation moves have been proper despite
criticism that its tight-money policy could topple the country into
a recession, .
   Greenspan told the House Budget Committee on Thursday that he did
not believe forcing the country into a recession was a proper way to
fight inflation and he said that was not the Fed's intention.
   But he said if the central bank had not been pursuing a policy of
gradually pushing up interest rates since March of last year,
inflationary pressures would be much more severe at the current time.
   If inflation gets out of control, the Fed is forced to squeeze
credit much tighter, driving interest rates even higher and making
any economic downturn much more severe.
   That is what occurred in 1981-82, when the country suffered
through the most drastic recession since the Great Depression, as
then-Fed Chairman Paul Volcker drove interest rates higher and
higher to combat the worst bout of inflation since the Civil War.
   Greenspan indicated that the Fed's current course was aimed at
making sure that the next recession will not have to be as severe.
   ``I do believe that the business cycle has not been repealed,''
Greenspan said. ``We will at some point get a recession, but I hope
that we have correct policies in place so the recession will be
mild.''
   Committee Chairman Leon Panetta, D-Calif., noted that there was a
difference of opinion on the Fed's credit-tightening moves, which
included a decision last Friday to boost to 7 percent the discount
rate, the interest the central bank charges to make loans to
financial institutions.
   ``Opinion seems divided whether this move was `too little, too
late' or `too much, too soon,' '' Panetta said.
   Panetta said that regardless of whether the higher interest rates
end up pushing the country into a recession, the credit tightening
will have many adverse consequences, including a bigger budget
deficit, more troubles for the savings and loan industry, higher
debt payments by Third World countries and higher costs to consumers
who borrow to purchase homes and autos.
   But Greenspan said the central bank remained convinced that the
dangers of doing nothing outweighed risks to specific sectors of the
economy from higher interest rates.
   On another matter, Greenspan said he still supported increasing
the federal gasoline tax but only as a conservation measure, not as
a way of boosting federal revenues.
   Greenspan also said that boosting taxes on alcoholic beverages
and cigarettes would not harm the economy, but he said simply
increasing federal tax revenues was not the answer the government's
imbalance between spending and revenues.
   Echoing a position taken by President Bush and former President
Reagan, Greenspan said that higher federal revenues were much more
likely to end up funding new programs rather than being used to
reduce the budget deficit.
   ``There is a tendency in Congress, when revenues are available,
to increase government programs,'' Greenspan said.
   Greenspan said he would prefer across-the-board spending cuts to
tax increases if Congress and the administration fail to agree on a
plan to reduce the 1990 budget deficit to $100 billion.
   Greenspan repeated warnings that he has made in earlier
congressional appearances that it is crucial that Congress and the
new administration reach agreement on a credible, multi-year plan to
reduce the budget deficit.
   He said there was ``no question'' that such a deficit-reduction
program would encourage financial investors and allow long-term
interest rates to fall substantially.
</TEXT>
