<FIRST>r w PM-SuperfundAssistance     03-03 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Superfund Assistance,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Criticizes EPA Handling of Grants for Community Groups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency is making
it difficult for citizen groups near Superfund hazardous waste sites
to participate in a grant program, a congressional report says.
   The program, which provides up to $50,000 in grants for community
groups to hire technical experts, isn't working, Rep. Jim Florio,
D-N.J., said Thursday after releasing the report with Rep. Edward J.
Markey, D-Mass.
   While some community groups described EPA staff as helpful to
applicants, ``many more commented that they were actively
discouraged from applying or expressed the belief that the agency
could not be interested ... based on the cumbersome process it had
established,'' the report said.
   The report, based on a survey of 72 people and community groups,
concluded the Technical Assistance Grant program was plagued by a
long application process, difficult-to-understand forms and EPA
staff resistance.
   Walter Kovalick Jr., deputy director of EPA's Office of Emergency
and Remedial Response, said, ``Trying to empower citizen groups is a
very difficult task when trying to balance fiscal responsibility and
being as helpful as we can to community groups.''
   He said EPA is trying to improve the program, and emphasized it
was not agency policy to discourage participation.
   Grants are available at each of the 1,175 Superfund hazardous
waste sites, so that community groups can get the technical
information needed for a voice in cleanup operations.
   Kovalick said 13 grants have been awarded so far, and the EPA is
considering an additional 79 letters expressing interest.
   The survey found that under the program, created in 1986:
   _More than 90 percent of the community groups encountered ``major
problems'' with the application process, with 9 out of 10 applicants
reporting difficulty in completing paperwork. One out of four
applicants spent more than six weeks filling out the applications.
   _EPA required that communities pay 35 percent of the technical
assistance costs, although Congress recommended only a 20 percent
matching requirement.
   _The agency agreed to waive the cost-sharing requirement only in
exceptional circumstances, while Congress wanted waivers whenever
needed to foster public participation.
   The report blamed the cumbersome application process for
``discouraging affected groups from participating'' in the program,
and added that the 35 percent community share makes the program
``insurmountable'' for many community organizations.
   Kovalick said EPA was given discretion to choose the matching
contribution for communities, and felt that by setting the figure at
35 percent, there would be more federal money to spread around.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
