<FIRST>r i PM-India-Fire     03-03 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Fire,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>25 Feared Dead In Fire, Stampede At Industrial Parade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 25 people were feared killed in
a fire and stampede today when flames engulfed a tent during
celebrations honoring the founder of one of India's largest
industrial companies, news agencies reported.
   Press Trust of India said at least 25 men, women and children
died in the blaze in Jamshedpur, a steel town 140 miles west of
Calcutta. United News of India said at least 25 were feared dead and
50 suffered severe injuries.
   The news agencies said the fire broke out in a big tent jammed
with spectators watching a parade at the Tata Iron and Steel Co.
   Press Trust of India said about 30,000 people watching the parade
tried to flee as flames shot into the sky.
   United News of India said winds fanned the flames before fire
trucks arrived. The news agency said the cause of the fire was not
yet known, but police suspected an electrical short circuit.
   Neither agency said whether the fire was under control.
   The parade was part of festivities marking the 150th anniversary
of the birth of Sir Jamshedji Tata, for whom the city is named.
   The Tata plant, built in 1912, is one of India's largest
producers of steel.
   Sir Jamshedji launched an industrial empire that today
encompasses luxury hotels, textile mills and manufacturing plants
that turn out trucks and buses, watches, telephones, cosmetics and
several other products.
   Many of the buses and big trucks in India bear the Tata logo, and
the heavy vehicles also are exported to many Asian and Middle
Eastern countries.
</TEXT>
