<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-03 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partial Solar Eclipse Next Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Naval Observatory says the view of the
sun for millions of Americans will be partially obscured when they
awaken next Tuesday morning.
   Residents of Hawaii and about the western two-thirds of the
United States and Canada will be able to see the eclipse, which will
be at its maximum at about 10 a.m. PST, according to calculations
reported by the Observatory on Thursday.
   For residents of Alaska, about 70 percent of the sun will be
covered during the eclipse, while less of the sun will be blocked
for viewers in other areas, according to astronomers at McDonald
Observatory of the University of Texas at Austin.
   The eclipse will occur as the new moon passes between the sun and
the Earth.
</TEXT>
