<HEAD>Accused Man Goes To Paraguay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department says a Philadelphia man
facing deportation following claims that he killed Jews during World
War II already has left the United States.
   George Theodorovich, 66, withdrew his appeal of a deportation
order with immigration authorities after obtaining a visa to travel
to Paraguay, the department said Thursday.
   Theodorovich, a retired meat cutter, was ordered deported in 1987
by an immigration judge after Justice produced reports that he had
written to account for bullets he used to shoot Jews as a member of
the Ukrainian police during Nazi occupation in the city of Lvov.
   Theodorovich was ordered deported to Argentina but the case was
before the Board of Immigration Appeals when Theodorovich fled to
Paraguay on Dec. 18, 1988.
   The Justice Department was not notified that Theodorovich had
fled the country until this week when it received papers filed by
his attorney with the immigration appeals board.
