<FIRST>r i PM-China-MarriedMen     03-03 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Married Men,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marriage Reported Between Two Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men, an army veteran and a farmer, were
recently married in a traditional ceremony in rural China, according
to an official report.
   The weekly Press Digest said in a report, available today, that
local authorities are trying to break up the ``marriage'' and that
the ex-soldier, who has acknowledged he is a homosexual, has been
fired from his job.
   It said Ye Xing, 26, a decorated four-year veteran of the
People's Liberation Army, married Li Linxing, 30, on Jan. 10.
   Nearly 100 friends and relatives were invited to the ceremony and
banquet in coastal Fujian province, it said.
   The report said Ye was twice honored as a model soldier and was
employed in the family planning office in his hometown in Zhouning
County after leaving the army three years ago.
   The township government and the department of public health are
now trying to separate the two and Ye was fired from his job, but
the pair is still living together with Li's family, it said.
   China's state-controlled media rarely reports on homosexuals.
There is virtually no open homosexuality in China, although there
are gathering places for foreign and Chinese homosexuals in more
Westernized cities such as Canton and Shanghai.
   Homosexuality is not a crime in China, but it is widely regarded
as immoral and socially unacceptable. Homosexuals are branded as
mentally disturbed.
</TEXT>
