<FIRST>r a BC-TankerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0468 03-03 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Tanker Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tanker Runs Aground Near Honolulu</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Restores dropped word in 6th graf, `The refinery...' ^By STEVE
ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker carrying 90,000 barrels of crude oil ran
aground in stormy seas off the Hawaiian island of Oahu, officials
said. Initial reports indicated as much as 8,400 gallons of oil had
spilled.
   Keith Spangler, a Coast Guard spokesman, said the 800-foot tanker
Exxon Houston sent a distress call at 8:20 p.m. Thursday.
   The 80,000-ton tanker reported it was ``hard aground''
three-tenths of a mile northwest of Barbers Point, an area on Oahu's
southwest coast about 15 miles west of the island's densely
populated area containing Honolulu, Spangler said.
   ``They said they've suffered some damage, but they don't know how
much yet,'' Spangler said.
   The Exxon Houston was offloading oil at about 5:25 p.m. at the
Hawaiian Independent Refinery when a mooring line broke, causing the
offloading hoses to break, said Andrea Simpson, a spokeswoman for
Pacific Resources Inc., the refinery's parent company.
   The refinery's valves automatically shut down the flow of oil, so
only about 8,400 gallons of the 90,000 barrels carried by the tanker
might have spilled, Simpson said.
   Simpson said the Coast Guard had reported that the high seas were
dissipating the oil spill.
   The Clean Island Council, a cooperative of oil handling companies
in Hawaii, planned to have crews out at first light to assess the
spill and begin any cleanup that might be needed, Simpson said.
   Spangler said environmental specialists from the Coast Guard's
Marine Safety Office were headed to the scene.
</TEXT>
