<FIRST>r a PM-Venezuela-Florida     03-03 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela-Florida,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela's Woes Concern Exporters Who Sell $1.5 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Venezuela, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Gimenez is cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela pumps about $1.5 billion a year into
Florida's economy, and business leaders are concerned that civil
unrest and economic woes in the South American nation could disrupt
their lucrative trade.
   Hundreds of people have been killed or injured in riots this week
in the wake of government-ordered price hikes in Venezuela. The
underlying economic problems are expected to make it harder for that
nation to import goods in the near future.
   Venezuela, which has had a relatively high standard of living in
the past decade because of an infusion of oil money, is Florida's
biggest export market for items like personal computers, software
and car and boat parts.
   ``About 40 percent of Florida's exports go to Venezuela,'' said
Jose Gimenez, president of the Venezuela Chamber of Commerce in
Miami. ``You can mention any item and it's probably there.''
   The rioting may not have an immediate impact on trade, but
Gimenez said he believes it signals an end to the glory days of
Venezuela's consumer economy.
   ``Venezuela has been living in a subsidized cocoon for 25 years.
Now it hurts to come out into the open,'' Gimenez said.
   Florida bankers were expecting a decline in trade with Venezuela
even before the unrest because of that country's falling foreign
currency reserves and its decision to impose a substantial 60
percent tariff on many imported goods.
</TEXT>
