in south Lebanon between Israeli troops and four Palestine
Liberation Organization guerrillas showed the organization is
``making fun of its promise to stop terrorism.''
   Officials said the four guerrillas, who were killed, had been
trying to infiltrate Israel on a hostage-taking mission.
   ``Despite the explicit PLO promise to the United States that it
would stop terror actions against Israel, the infiltration attempt
is a decisive proof that this terrorist organization is carrying out
terror acts,'' Shamir told the daily Yediot Ahronot.
   The United States opened direct contacts with the PLO in December
after PLO chairman Yasser Arafat said he was renouncing terrorism
and recognizing Israel.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said today that the latest
infiltration attempt violated the U.S conditions.
   Asked whether Israel was trying to persuade Washington to end the
contacts, Liel said: ``We are forwarding the information regarding
these attacks on a regular basis to the United States, but they
should draw their own conclusions.''
