<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0547EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AnthraxHearing     03-03 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anthrax Hearing,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Town Board Cancels Hearing, Quaker Group Holds Alternative
Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last-minute cancellation of a town
Health Board hearing on military-funded anthrax research at the
University of Massachusetts didn't deter a Quaker group from
expressing its opposition.
   ``We feel the issue is of extreme importance and we will not back
down just because of a decision they have made in the last 24
hours,'' said John Bonifaz, who is organizing efforts by the local
branch of the American Friends Service Committee to stop the
research.
   The Quakers claim the 23-year-old research project poses a health
threat to the nation as well as Amherst because its findings could
be used for military purposes. The group went ahead with its own
meeting Thursday after the Health Board hearing it had requested was
canceled.
   Anthrax is an infectious disease contracted by wild and
domesticated animals, especially cattle and sheep. It is caused by a
bacterium and can be transmitted to people.
   The chief scientist on the research project, Curtis B. Thorne,
has maintained his work on the basic structure of the bacterium is
aimed at finding a vaccine for the disease.
   Town Manager Barry DelCastilho said he canceled the hearing after
a town attorney warned him that two of the board's four members work
at the university, posing a conflict of interest. He said he hoped
to appoint a fifth member to the board soon to make a quorum for a
hearing.
   At the meeting, Bonifaz's group presented a draft regulation that
would ban military biological research. Others spoke to urge the
board to stop the research, which is funded by the Department of
Defense.
   ``Research conducted under contract with the Department of
Defense has military and not public health objectives. It is the
military contract for this research that is of concern to us,'' said
Nachama Wilker, director of the Council for Responsible Genetics in
Boston.
   University officials didn't attend the meeting. Chancellor Joseph
Duffey has argued that the strain of bacteria being tested is
non-virulent and has been under study for 23 years without incident.
He also said the school's policy is to allow Defense Department
research as long as it is unclassified.
</TEXT>
