<FIRST>r a PM-PaulaCooper     03-03 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Paula Cooper,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Supporters Visit 19-Year-Old On Death Row</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATTY REINERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Italian opponents of capital
punishment tried to boost the spirits of a 19-year-old woman who is
sitting on death row while the Indiana Supreme Court decides her
fate.
   ``We tried to ease her tension because it's not easy to wait for
a piece of paper that's telling you that you have to die or not,''
said Rev. Vito Bracone after a three-hour visit with Paula Cooper at
the Indiana Women's Prison.
   ``We tried to assure her that we'll be always with her.''
   Bracone is a member of the Italian group ``Thou Shall Not Kill''
that has been protesting Cooper's sentence for two years in Italy,
where the case has received much attention.
   The group planned to travel to New York to deliver petitions to
the United Nations today before returning to Italy.
   Cooper is the youngest female in the United States sentenced to
death. She was 15 in 1985 when she and three other Gary teen-agers
robbed and killed Ruth Elizabeth Pelke, a 78-year-old retired Bible
teacher. Pelke was stabbed at least 30 times with a butcher knife.
   The state high court on Wednesday heard oral arguments in her
appeal and has not indicated when it will issue a decision.
   At the time of Cooper's sentencing, Indiana law allowed the death
penalty for anyone over the age of 10 convicted of murder. The age
limit has since been raised to 16, but was not made retroactive.
   Cooper's lawyer, William L. Touchette, described his client as
``relaxed and happy'' after meeting the Italians.
   ``There's a lot of anticipation sitting there waiting. It's not
the easiest thing in the world to do,'' Touchette said. ``But it's
like finally it's starting to come to a conclusion _ maybe _ for
her.''
   Touchette said he's optimistic that the Supreme Court will
commute his client's death sentence. ``I'm hopeful, always
hopeful,'' he said.
   In a handwritten note to The Associated Press, Cooper refused to
grant interviews with the U.S. media.
   ``She doesn't want any negative publicity,'' said Patti Wolter,
an investigator who has worked on the case with Touchette. ``She's
afraid of doing or saying something that's going to influence public
opinion.''
</TEXT>
