<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BeachesBeware     03-03 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Beaches Beware,0447</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warning: Rio Beaches Could Be Hazardous To Your Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Think twice before setting foot on
the beaches of Rio de Janeiro.
   Thousands of hungry little parasites are waiting hidden in the
sand.
   A city study of Rio's beaches that was released earlier this week
says those chic beaches pictured on postcards and in international
travel magazines are hardly pristine. In fact, the report warns,
they're downright contaminated.
   ``The sand is the dirtiest it's ever been on record,'' said
Carlos Mora, spokesman for Rio's sanitation department, which
conducted the study.
   The study, conducted last month and released Tuesday, found the
sand of the toniest of Rio's beaches _ Copacabana, Leme, Ipanema and
Leblon _ is packed with nine types of parasites carried in animal
and human feces. Among them is the potentially fatal esquistossomose
parasite, which afflicts 8 million Brazilians.
   ``We don't want to create a panic,'' Mayor Marcello Alencar said
when he announced the study's findings. ``But the public ought to
know what is happening in its city.''
   Rio's beaches, polluted in the past by chemical waste from
factories and by occasional breaks in sewage lines along the
beachfront, have new enemies now. They are stray animals and
homeless beggars who bed down on the beaches, as well as hordes of
street vendors in make-shift shacks along the shore.
   A week ago, in an effort to clean up the beaches, police
officials raided Copacabana and hauled off hundreds of dollars worth
of merchandise from the illegal stands parked on the beach and along
the boardwalk.
   But the peddlers and the animals returned the next day _ with a
vengeance. And the beaches took another drubbing.
   ``You wouldn't catch me taking my kids to these beaches,'' said
Mora. ``The city has forgotten that it has to protect to beaches,
not just rave about how pretty they are.''
   He said that compared with a year ago, when the beaches were last
tested for pollution, the beaches ``had gotten a lot worse.''
   Despite the findings, some health experts were skeptical of the
potential health threat to sunseekers.
   ``The sun kills the parasites on the surface,'' said Dr. Carlos
Albeto de Freitas, a disease control expert for the city. ``The
danger lies in the deeper sand.''
   Still, the possibility of catching a disease from the sand is
greater than in past years.
   ``People just ought to be careful they don't dig their feet too
far under the sand,'' de Freitas said. ``Otherwise, they might go
home with more than a nice tan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
