<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral     03-03 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vrdolyak Unofficial Winner In Chicago GOP Mayoral Primary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In eight days, political maverick Edward Vrdolyak
has come out of hiding, unofficially won the Republican mayoral
primary and posed a potential threat to Richard M. Daley's bid to
get his father's old job.
   Vrdolyak, a write-in candidate, has not been declared the
official victor of Tuesday's Republican primary, but Thursday's
canvass by the Chicago Board of Election Commissioners found him
ahead, 11,621 to 10,478 over Herbert Sohn.
   ``If people can spell the name Vrdolyak, or close to it, and
write it in, I mean, it was just wonderful,'' said the joyous
ex-Democrat, a former alderman whose combative style is guaranteed
to add spice to the campaign that leads to the April 4 general
election.
   His apparent victory sets up a three-way battle for mayor:
Vrdolyak, Democratic nominee Richard M. Daley _ both white _ and
Timothy Evans, a black alderman running as an independent.
   The scenario is similar to the 1983 Democratic primary, in which
Daley and incumbent Jane Byrne split the white vote, allowing Harold
Washington to score a narrow victory on the way to eventually
becoming the city's first black mayor.
   The winner of the April 4 election fills the final two years of
the four-year term won by Washington, who died seven months after
winning the April 1987 election.
   Paul Kleppner, a Northern Illinois University professor who has
analyzed Chicago voting trends for the U.S. Justice Department,
downplayed the significance of Vrdolyak's candidacy and predicted a
Daley triumph.
   ``Vrdolyak will only draw white votes away (from Daley) if people
are sure they're not endangering the chance of a white candidate
winning,'' Kleppner said.
   Still, said analyst Tom Roesser, active in local GOP circles,
Vrdolyak's vote-drawing power far outstrips Sohn's.
   ``Eddie can't win, but he could cause some real mischief,''
Roesser said.
   Daley, son of 21-year Mayor Richard J. Daley, is vacationing in
Florida, but his chief campaign strategist, David Axelrod, said
Vrdolyak's influence on the election ``will be negligible.''
   Four of the city's 2,911 precincts remained to be counted and
after another review, the winner of the GOP primary will be
officially declared on Tuesday.
   Sohn, who was endorsed by the local Republican Party, held out
hope he could still be declared the GOP nominee and his aides
suggested the courts may make the final decision.
   Vrdolyak, the former chairman of the Cook County Democratic
Party, has lost his last two tries for office. He ran as an
independent for mayor in 1987, then became a Republican and sought
the office of clerk of the county court system last November.
   After the November defeat, he was rarely seen in public and gave
few interviews to the news media. But on Feb. 22, less than a week
before the Republican primary, he appeared at a rally and said he
would run as a write-in candidate for mayor at the urging of his
admirers.
</TEXT>
