<FIRST>r a PM-RevolutionaryCannon     03-03 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Revolutionary Cannon,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battle of Bunker Hill Cannon Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the four cannons that were all the 13
colonies had when the Revolutionary War started has been found in
the basement of a police station, ending a search that began nearly
20 years ago.
   ``It is a priceless piece of history which could be called a
national treasure,'' Capt. Albert Swanson, Metrolopitan District
Commission historian, said after cannon was found Thursday.
   The 3{-foot-long, 500-pound brass cannon, believed to have been
forged in London around 1760, was found behind dozens of bicycles in
a storage room that was being cleaned at the Metropolitan Police's
Lower Basin station.
   Swanson said it was used in the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17,
1775. Two of the four cannons the colonies had at the start of the
Revolutionary War were captured by the British.
   But the rediscovered cannon, now called the Hancock, and the
other, now called the Adams, were hidden in a swamp in Dedham,
Swanson said.
   The Hancock and the Adams were placed at the Bunker Hill Monument
during the 19th century. The Metropolitan District Commission was in
charge of the monument from 1919 until the National Park Service
took it over in 1975.
   ``When we took the site over in `75, there was one cannon tube
(the Adams) left at the top,'' said Peter Steele, curator of the
monument.
   ``They were a pair. We contacted the MDC about the missing one,
but no one was able to put their fingers on it. I had pretty much
given up hope. This is great news.''
   Swanson said he knew the cannon had been brought to the police
station but no one could tell him where it was, and he had been
keeping an eye out for it for 18 years. He and Steele thought it had
been taken from the monument in 1970 or 1972.
   ``What apparently happened is that a bracket holding the cannon
broke,'' Swanson said. ``It was brought to the station for
safekeeping.''
   Swanson said he hopes the cannon will be refurbished and placed
in new brackets at the monument by June 17, Bunker Hill Day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-TeamSpirit     03-03 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Team Spirit,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., South Korea Announce Exercises Despite Protests From North</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and South Korea today
announced plans for large-scale joint military exercises despite
warnings from communist North Korea that the maneuvers could wreck
prospects for peace talks.
   The U.S. Eighth Army said about 200,000 U.S. and South Korean
troops, along with air force and navy units, would participate in
the annual ``Team Spirit'' exercises beginning March 14. About
70,000 U.S. troops are to take part.
   North Korea warned Thursday during talks with South Korean
delegates that ``Team Spirit'' must be abandoned if the two sides
are to make progress on easing tension across the divided peninsula.
North Korean officials charged ``Team Spirit'' was preparation for a
nuclear attack on the North.
   North Korea has been demanding a halt to ``Team Spirit'' for
several months and today's announcement in Seoul could be used by
the North to end all talks with the capitalist South. There was no
immediate reaction from the North today.
   South Korean officials said they hoped North Korea would continue
talks on improving relations, but that the exercises are vital to
the South's defenses. The North maintains far larger military forces
than the South and seriously threatens South Korea's safety, they
said.
   North Korea keeps armed forces estimated at 840,000 troops; South
Korea has about 600,000 of its own forces in addition to U.S. forces.
   North Korea and China will be invited to send observers to the
exercises to show there was no hostile intention, U.S. officials
said. The North has rejected similar offers in the past.
   North Korea pulled out of peace talks with South Korea in 1986
after Seoul refused to end ``Team Spirit'' that year. U.S. officials
said the North might do the same thing this year.
   North Korean and South Korean delegates failed to make progress
Thursday on setting terms for talks between their prime ministers
after the North said ``Team Spirit'' must be called off before the
opening of substantive negotiations. The two sides agreed to meet
again April 12.
   U.S. and South Korean officials said ``Team Spirit'' was being
held for the 14th consecutive year as a purely defensive exercise
that poses no threat to the North.
   ``The purpose is to train American and South Korean forces to
defend Korea. It's never threatened North Korea in the past, and
there is no threat this time,'' said a U.S. military spokesman on
condition of anonymity.
   The exercises will be on the same scale as in 1988, the U.S.
spokesman said.
   The soldiers will practice reinforcing South Korean units with
U.S. troops in the event of a North Korean attack. The United States
has about 42,000 troops based in the South under a mutual defense
treaty, and about 30,000 others will come from the United States to
take part in the maneuvers.
   The exercise will involve U.S. ground forces, including units
based on the American West Coast, along with major U.S. Navy and
U.S. Air Force units.
   U.S. military officials stressed today that the exercises would
be held far away from the North Korean border to avoid any risk of
an accidental confrontation. The main exercises will be held March
14-23.
   The two Koreas are archrivals with hundreds of thousands of
troops facing each other along their 150-mile border. The North
invaded the South in 1950, launching the Korean War. They are
technically still at war because no peace treaty was signed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0803 03-03 0774</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0803,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Lend Me A Tenor,' A New Farce, Opens On Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS three grafs of other reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farce is built on desperation, and things don't
get more desperate than the doings at the Cleveland Grand Opera
Company, circa 1934.
   Its gala benefit performance of ``Otello'' is threatened by the
apparent demise of famed Italian tenor _ and unrepentant ladies' man
_ Tito Merelli. The company, along with 50 pounds of shrimp
mayonnaise, may expire unless someone can be found quickly to
replace the man known to his adoring fans as ``Il Stupendo.''
   That is the basic setup for ``Lend Me a Tenor,'' a new farce by
Ken Ludwig that barreled into Broadway's Royale Theater on Thursday
night. Although the play is slight, the evening is still delirium
triumphant, primarily because of the crackerjack direction of Jerry
Zaks and a superb cast led by Victor Garber and Philip Bosco.
   You'll know ``Lend Me a Tenor'' is a farce the minute the curtain
rises on six smashing art deco doors scattered throughout designer
Tony Walton's all-white hotel suite. They are waiting to be slammed.
And Zaks sees that they are _ in high, often hilarious, style.
   Tito, of course, is not dead. He's sleeping off a combination of
red wine and phenobarbital. But neither the opera company manager
(Bosco) nor his milquetoast assistant Max (Garber) knows that.
   Max, a frustrated opera performer, rises to Tito's high C.
Slapping on blackface, a shaggy wig and the singer's purple tights,
he goes on for the star, and no one knows the difference. When Tito
wakes up, he dons an identical costume _ didn't you know he would
carry a spare _ and suddenly there are two tenors and glorious
confusion.
   Much of the fun is physical rather than verbal _ Garber mixing a
drink with his finger, Bosco attacking a bowl of wax fruit or Garber
desperately trying to wake up the horizontal tenor. Zaks'
inventiveness is astonishing. He has to work hard with Ludwig's
script. Some of the jokes are obvious, unsurprising laughs, but Zaks
does his best to divert attention from these dips in dialogue.
   Still, there are some very funny situations, particularly in the
second act. The opera disguise allows Max to change his personality.
He becomes forceful and is able to conquer the opera manager's
daughter. She's looking for a fling but only wants to be flung by
Tito. Garber is all bumbling sweetness, a Walter Mitty who discovers
his voice and confidence at the same time.
   If Garber is all mumbles, Bosco is all roar. The actor raises
apoplexy to high art, particularly in one scene when he throws
himself in a rage at Tito's inert body. Seldom has such fury been so
funny.
   Ron Holgate can't quite hold onto his Italian accent, but
everything else is just about right in his performance as the
over-inflated Tito. He's even a fine singer. And he's perfectly
matched with Tovah Feldshuh as his jealous wife who one minute is a
purring pussycat, the next a snarling panther.
   J. Smith-Cameron is fetching as the ingenue, a stereotypical role
that usually is more simpering than sexy. Jane Connell charges
merrily through the play as the chairman of the opera guild and
there is other good support by Caroline Lagerfelt as an amorous
soprano and Jeff Brooks as an operatic bellhop.
   The glamorous costumes by William Ivey Long epitomize the 1930s.
Some of them are even funny, particularly an evening gown for Miss
Connell that makes her, in the words of another character, ``look
like the Chrysler Building.''
   ``Lend Me a Tenor'' isn't Feydeau _ not much is these days,
particularly on Broadway. But it is great fun, particularly because
of Zaks orchestrating all those slamming doors.
   In other reviews:
   ``Sheer craziness'' is how Clive Barnes of the New York Post
described the play. ``If you are feeling under the weather _ or even
over the weather, for that matter _ and you believe laughter is the
best medicine, let me prescribe for you this lovely dose of pure,
operatic idiocy.''
   Howard Kissel in the Daily News called the play enjoyable ``under
Jerry Zaks brilliant direction,'' although he noted that ``the plot
would not withstand intense scrutiny.''
   But in The New York Times, Frank Rich said the play was ``all
things farcical except hilarious.... The lines are almost never
witty, settling instead for double entendres ... (and) worse, too
many of the farcical situations seem like pale echoes of those in
similar works from the play's period.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
