<FIRST>r i PM-AIDS-WHO     03-03 0195</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-WHO,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>First AIDS Cases Reported In Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran recorded its first five cases of AIDS last
year, the World Health Organization said today in its latest health
update.
   The Islamic republic's report was among 2,008 new cases reported
to WHO last month, bringing the total to 141,894 AIDS cases in 145
countries. Thirty-two countries said they had no cases, according to
WHO's monthly epidemiological report for February.
   While not previously mentioning AIDS cases, Iran has reported
that nearly 450 hemophiliacs, or 14 percent of the country's known
hemophiliac total, carry the AIDS virus.
   The United States, which has 60 percent of all AIDS victims,
accounts for most of the new cases reported to WHO in February _
1,654. The U.S. total rose to 86,157 victims as of Feb. 16, WHO said.
   West Germany, which has the third-highest total in Europe after
France and Italy, reported 106 cases for a new total of 2,885. The
Netherlands reported 43 new cases, Britain 67, and South Africa 45.
   For Iran, the new WHO bulletin listed five cases as of Dec. 31.
Last month's bulletin showed no cases in Iran on Dec. 31, 1987.
</TEXT>
