<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0701EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionProtesters     03-03 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Protesters,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appellate Court Upholds Protesters' RICO Violation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court upheld a decision
that 26 anti-abortion activists had violated racketeering laws with
their protests, a ruling one lawyer said ``strikes a blow at the
very heart'' of the anti-abortion movement.
   Abortion foes and their lawyers attacked the decision, calling it
a serious setback for people who practice civil disobedience.
   A three-judge panel of the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on
Thursday upheld a lower court decision that the protesters violated
racketeering laws by conspiring to prevent abortions at Northeast
Women's Center Inc., a Philadelphia clinic. The court also awarded
about $110,000 in damages and attorneys' fees to the center.
   The center's lawsuit was the first test of the federal Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act in a civil case against
abortion demonstrators, said Edmond A. Tiryak, the lawyer who
brought the action for the clinic.
   ``From our point of view, this is an important example that will
be used nationally,'' he said. The lawsuit has been used as a model
by other clinics in as many as 11 other cases still at the trial
level, he said.
   The center had charged that the protesters used force, threats
and trespassing to intimidate center employees and women seeking
abortions.
   ``What's been going on at the center has been intimidation and
fear,'' said Tiryak. ``This opinion, I think, strikes a blow at the
very heart of that activity by the pro-life movement.''
   An anti-abortion leader named in the suit lambasted the decision
but predicted it wouldn't stop future demonstrations.
   ``The American judicial system has taken a vengeance against
anyone who tries to stand up for children in the womb,'' said
Michael McMonagle, executive director of the Pro-Life Coalition of
Southeast Pennsylvania.
   Nevertheless, he said that since the lawsuit was filed in 1987,
``the rescue movement has taken off the ground, and RICO suits can't
stop it now.''
   The RICO Act has most often been used against organized crime
figures, but Tiryak said it was applicable in the case because
protesters used extortion _ in the form of threats and force _ to
deny the center its right to operate and to deny women their right
to use the center.
   The appelate panel unanimously upheld a June 1987 finding by a
federal district jury that the protesters had engaged in a pattern
of criminal activity from 1984 to 1986 designed to prevent the
center from providing abortions.
   The appeals court said videotapes made by the center ``revealed
demonstrators pushing, shoving and tugging on patients as they
attempted to approach the center, knocking over and crossing police
barricades and blocking the ingress of cars.''
   The court rejected the protesters' argument that their actions
were justified because of the issue, saying they could have used
numerous legal alternatives to persuade women not to have abortions
``short of harassment.''
   Tiryak contended the center lost its lease and was forced to move
because of the protests.
   McMonagle claimed no protester was ever charged with assault,
even though police were present at the demonstrations.
   ``Pushing doesn't make a racketeer, doesn't make extortionist,''
he said.
   McMonagle said the protesters will request that the full appeals
court review the decision by the three-judge panel.
   The appeals court ordered the district court to further consider
injunctions the center is seeking to limit the number of
demonstrators outside the center and prohibit them from using
bullhorns.
   Meanwhile, a federal judge in Los Angeles issued a temporary
restraining order barring the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue
from blockading women's health clinics in California during its
planned Easter week protests.
   U.S. District Judge Terry Hatter's order, which was sought by the
American Civil Liberties Union, instructs protesters to stay at
least 15 feet away from clinics.
   Operation Rescue leaders said they hoped to assemble 10,000
demonstrators in Los Angeles to blockade clinics from March 22-25.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
