<FIRST>u a PM-TankerAground 1stLd-Writethru a0495 03-03 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Aground, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Tanker Runs Aground Near Honolulu; Estimated 117,000 Gallons
Spilled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE estimate of spill to 117,000 gallons
sted 8,400, oil washing ashore, ADD quotes, details; picks up 4th graf
pvs, `Leonard Alcantara ...' DELETES 8th graf, `The refinery's ...' to
conform.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tanker carrying 90,000 barrels of crude oil ran
aground in stormy seas about 15 miles from Hawaii's most popular
tourist area, spilling an estimated 117,000 gallons of fuel oil and
crude into the water, officials said.
   Coast Guard spokesman Keith Spangler said the 800-foot tanker
Exxon Houston sent a distress call at 8:20 p.m. Thursday off the
Hawaiian island of Oahu.
   The captain of the tanker reported the ship was ``hard aground''
three-tenths of a mile northwest of Barbers Point on Oahu's
southwest coast, about 15 miles west of the island's densely
populated area containing Honolulu and Waikiki Beach, its most
popular tourist area, Spangler said.
   ``They've told us their fuel tanks were completedly emptied,''
Spangler said.
   He said an estimated 92,000 gallons of fuel oil had leaked
through holes in the tanker's hull and 25,000 gallons of crude oil
had spilled.
   Spangler said it wasn't clear whether the crude leaked when the
tanker broke loose from its moorings in 12-to-14-foot seas, or
whether it spilled through holes in the hull. Officials don't know
if crude is continuing to leak, he added.
   Spangler said the Oahu Civil Defense Agency reported early today
that fuel oil was washing ashore on the beach at Barbers Point.
However, he said the length of shoreline affected probably wouldn't
be known until daybreak.
   Winds and ocean currents should direct the spill east toward
Honolulu, Spangler said. Earlier Coast Guard reports said rough seas
appeared to be dissipating the oil.
   Leonard Alcantara, a Honolulu attorney for Exxon, said the ship's
captain, Kevin Dick, and the 23-member crew have remained aboard and
were in no danger.
   ``They said they've suffered some damage, but they don't know how
much yet,'' Spangler said.
   The Exxon Houston was unloading Alaska North Slope oil at the
Hawaiian Independent Refinery at about 5:25 p.m. when a mooring line
broke, causing the offloading hoses to break, said Andrea Simpson, a
spokeswoman for Pacific Resources Inc., the refinery's parent
company.
   The vessel reported trouble but did not request Coast Guard
assistance when it broke its moorings, Spangler said.
   A total of nine commercial and U.S. Navy tugboats were dispatched
to help dislodge the tanker, and environmental specialists also were
en route, officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
