<FIRST>r a PM-Eggs-Divorce     03-03 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eggs-Divorce,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wants Custody Of Frozen, Fertilized Eggs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KRISTI UMBREIT</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>MARYVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple in the midst of a divorce are
fighting for custody of the fertilized eggs they put in frozen
storage a few years ago.
   Junior Lewis Davis, 30, says he does not want his wife, Mary Sue
Davis, 28, to become pregnant, and a judge has issued an order
temporarily blocking her from having the embryos implanted.
   Despite Davis' divorce petition and his objection to becoming a
father, Mrs. Davis has said she eventually plans to have the eggs
implanted, according to the complaint.
   Davis contends that he and wife jointly own the fertilized eggs
and that any plans to use the frozen embryos to become pregnant _ as
late as several years from now _ have an impact on his life.
   Blount County Circuit Judge W. Dale Young has agreed, and on Feb.
23 he issued the order that also prohibits Mrs. Davis from removing
any of the eggs from frozen storage pending further hearings.
   Seven of the couple's fertilized eggs are stored at Fort Sanders
Regional Medical Center, the complaint said.
   Davis told The Associated Press on Thursday he had no comment.
   Mary Sue Davis did not return a telephone call made to the
Knoxville company where she works.
   Charles M. Clifford, Davis' Maryville lawyer, said he would not
comment on the case.
   In in-vitro fertilization, the woman's ova are surgically removed
and fertilized with sperm in a laboratory container, then implanted
in the woman's womb in hopes of a pregnancy.
   Great Britain pioneered the practice and produced the world's
first ``test-tube baby'' in 1978.
   Since then, other infertile couples have resorted to the method,
which costs between $4,000 and $10,000 and has an approximately 15
percent success rate for each implant.
</TEXT>
