<FIRST>r w AM-Embassies     03-03 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Embassies,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>US, Soviets Boosting Staffs at Embassies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and the Soviet Union have
agreed to increases in their embassy staffs, reversing a cutback
forced by the Reagan administration after reporter Nicholas Daniloff
was accused in Moscow of spying.
   Charles E. Redman, the State Department spokesman, said Friday
that 18 positions were added last month to the U.S. Embassy in the
Soviet capital and to the Soviet Embassy here, along with two
additional slots at the U.S. and Soviet consulates in Leningrad and
San Francisco.
   On Aug. 1, Redman said, 13 additional slots will be added to each
of the embassies and two more to the consulates. The maximums then
would be 256 for the embassies and 30 for the consulates.
   Daniloff's arrest _ he was subsequently released _ touched off a
diplomatic tiff in which the Reagan administration in October 1986
imposed ceilings of 225 at the embassies and 26 at the consulates.
   This forced the Soviets, which had a bigger staff, to withdraw
about 80 workers.
   Explaining the reversal, Redman said the workload at the U.S.
Embassy and consulate had increased. More visas are being issued for
Soviets emigrating and for those going to the United States on
cultural exchanges.
</TEXT>
