<FIRST>r w AM-Hijacking-Trial     03-03 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijacking-Trial,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hijacked Plane's Steward Says Younis Pretended to Kill Guards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A steward from a Jordanian jet hijacked in 1985
testified Friday that accused sky pirate Fawaz Younis threatened to
kill passengers and crew and tricked them into believing his men had
shot the plane's security guards.
   The steward, Omar Suliman El Ghadi, 32, was the fifth witness in
the trial at U.S. District Court to identify Younis as the leader of
five heavily armed men who stormed aboard Royal Jordanian Airlines
flight 402 in Beirut on June 11, 1985.
   In the initial moments of the hijacking, El Ghadi testified,
Younis ran to the front of the Boeing 727, pounded on the locked
cockpit door with his gun and shouted, ``If you don't open the door,
I will explode it.''
   The hijackers were armed with AK-47 assault rifles and hand
grenades, according to testimony from other witnesses and a
videotape taken at the end of the 30-hour ordeal.
   The testimony by El Ghadi was the first during the five-day trial
to portray Younis as directly threatening the passengers and crew
with death.
   Younis, 30, has pleaded innocent to a six-count indictment
stemming from the hijacking.
   He was captured by FBI agents in international waters in the
Mediterranean Sea more than two years after the hijacking, on Sept.
13, 1987, and the trial is seen as a test of a 1984 statute in which
U.S. authorities assert ``long-arm'' jurisdiction over the taking of
American hostages abroad.
   Near the end of the hijacking, El Ghadi testified, the sky
pirates told passengers and crew that at 7 a.m. the following
morning, they would ``start killing'' them, ``the security officers
first.''
   The hijackers removed jewelry from a female security officer, and
led all nine of them off the plane.
   ``We heard gunfire,'' testified El Ghadi.
   Younis, called Nazeeh by the other hijackers, came back aboard
and said, ``That's it. We killed the security and put their bodies
in the cargo of the airplane.''
   The security officers were not, in fact killed, and El Ghadi said
that when he saw them later in Jordan, ``I was shocked.''
   El Ghadi began his testimony by describing the early moments of
the hijacking, as gunshots were heard outside the plane, passengers
streamed inside, knocking the sky marshals off balance, and the
hijackers ran aboard.
   The steward testified that he refused orders from the hijackers
to close the door of the airplane for take-off, and that a few
moments later, Younis emerged from the cockpit ``slapping and
pushing'' the flight engineer to the rear to close the door.
   Another hijacker, called ``No. 2'' by El Ghadi, then began to
beat the female security guard and threatened her with a knife. El
Ghadi intervened.
   ``Hijacker No. 2 put his submachine gun at the back of my head''
and ordered him to search her, the steward testified.
   After refueling in Cyprus, the hijackers ordered the plane flown
to Tunis, where they wanted to read a statement demanding that
Palestinians be removed from Lebanon. Tunisian authorities blocked
the runways with trucks and the plane returned to Beirut.
   The sky marshals were taken off the plane, followed several hours
later by the passengers and crew, most of whom shook hands with the
Younis as they left.
   El Ghadi said he refused to shake hands and was again threatened
with death but was allowed to board a bus with the other passengers
and crew.
</TEXT>
