<FIRST>r a AM-FlagFlap     03-03 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Flap,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>School System Closes Early Due To Racial Tensions Over Rebel Flag</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATER VALLEY, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racial tensions sparked when several
white students waved Confederate flags during a black history
program prompted officials to close classes for spring vacation two
weeks early.
   ``We could tell this morning there was potential for disturbances
and decided to dismiss,'' school Superintendent Kenny Goodwin said
after students were sent home at 8:30 a.m. Friday.
   He said the week-long spring holiday would begin Monday instead
of March 20 and ``will be a cooling off period.''
   Authorities said no violence had been reported, but blacks had
walked off the football and baseball teams at the 600-student high
school and tensions were high.
   The problem developed Monday when several white students waved
Confederate flags during a program for black history month at the
high school. Goodwin said the five or six students who created the
disturbance had been disciplined but not all had been suspended.
   In protest of Monday's incident, black athletes began a boycott
of the football and baseball teams.
   Several black students interviewed after school Thursday said
they dropped out of sports activities because they were ``hurt by
what the white kids did.''
   Some of the whites involved in the flag incident were members of
the football team, said one black player who asked not to be
identified. ``We've been playing with them all this time and then
they do that. ... It hurt us,'' he said.
   The Oxford Eagle quoted sources close to the football and
baseball teams as saying most of the players were boycotting at the
request of their parents. One parent, who also asked not to be
identified, said athletes would not return to the teams ``until we
say they can.''
   About 60 parents of black students met Thursday night with
Goodwin and high school Principal Jerry Holt to discuss the problem.
Goodwin said no real progress was made but people ``got to vent
their frustrations.''
   ``There wasn't as much tension at school Thursday but things kind
of became inflamed late yesterday and last night,'' Goodwin said in
announcing his decision.
   He said school administrators would report for work next week
during the rescheduled holiday break and would be available to
discuss problems with parents and students.
</TEXT>
