<FIRST>u a PM-FloridaOilSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0581 03-03 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Florida Oil Spill, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0581,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Oil Spill Off Key Largo Sanctuaries</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with report spill is smaller,
farther away from reserves, not a threat. Picks up final graf pvs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An oil slick was spotted today off sensitive marine
reserves in the northern Florida Keys, but Coast Guard officials
said the spill did not appear to be a threat to the area.
   A flyover by Coast Guard officials found the slick was 2 miles
long and a quarter-mile wide, much smaller than first reported.
   ``It's not as bad as we feared,'' Coast Guard spokesman Joe Dye
said.
   Parks in the area reported small gobs of tar washing up, and said
there did not appear to be major damage.
   Dye said dead birds were found out near the oil, but it was not
clear if they were killed by the slick.
   A fisherman reported the oil just before 10 a.m., Dye said.
   ``We have no idea where it came from,'' he said. ``There are
apparently no ships in the area.''
   The Gulf Stream runs past Key Largo at that point, which means
the oil could have come north from Cuba or even farther away.
   The oil floated close to two sensitive north Key Largo marine
reserves _ the Key Largo National Marine Sanctuary and John
Pennekamp Coral Reef State Park.
   Pennekamp boasts the nation's only shallow-water living coral
reef, which also extends into the federal Key Largo reserves.
   Coast Guard and park officials will consult to decide whether to
order booms placed around the slick immediately and send boats to
clean up the oil, Dye said.
   Although the Coast Guard said the spill was 10 to 12 miles
offshore, there were reports of tar balls at the 120-square-mile Key
Largo reserve, said park spokeswoman Maddy Hoover.
   ``We don't know too much just yet, but we've gotten reports that
we've got crude oil and tar balls from the size of baseballs to the
size of grapefruit,'' she said.
   The 20-mile-long reserve stretches north from Molasses Point off
the Atlantic shore of Key Largo, and includes the area outside the
3-mile limit, while Pennekamp includes the shoreline and out to the
3-mile limit in some of the same areas, she said.
</TEXT>
