<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia     03-03 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Gov't Workers Struggle to Flee War-Torn Tigray</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEGE MBITIRU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government troops and workers ordered to
abandon war-torn northern Ethiopia to rebels, were stranded Friday
for lack of transport, an African diplomat said.
   ``I understand it will take them a long time before they can
return,'' the foreign envoy said in a telephone interview from
Ethiopia's capital, Addis Ababa.
   If troops, civil servants and other officials abandon Tigray
province, as ordered Monday by the government, that would leave the
administration with no overland access to Eritrea, the extreme
northern province that has the East African nation's only ports. The
government still is flying planes into Assab and Massawa, its main
ports on the Red Sea.
   The retreat follows a series of rebel victories which the
government referred to indirectly Thursday in a statement urging
Ethiopians ``to be ready for an active involvement in every area of
the armed struggle.''
   ``No nation can tolerate violence, and there is no alternative
now except to join hands and diffuse the aggression launched against
the Ethiopian people,'' said the statement, published by the
official Ethiopian News Agency.
   The diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he did
not know if rebels have moved into towns in northern Tigray province
evacuated by the government.
   ``There are no government troops fighting there,'' he said.
``Even those who are left are in southern Tigray. There are no
government officials in the north.''
   The government did not refer directly to Tuesday reports by
insurgents that the government had evacuated Tigray's provincial
capital, Mekele, ``fearing humiliating and shaking defeat as in Enda
Selassie and surrounding areas.''
   Enda Selassie is near Mekele, 475 miles northwest of Addis Ababa.
   ``The whole of Tigray is now liberated from the fascist regime of
Mengistu,'' rebel spokesman Yemane Kidane told a reporter in Sudan's
capital, Khartoum.
   The government said ``the secessionist TPLF and the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front had coordinated attacks against Ethiopian
army along Adwa, Aksum and Enda Selassie route with the view to
dismember the Ethiopian Red Sea area from the rest of the country.''
   Kidane said Tigrean rebels destroyed Ethiopia's 206th army corps,
killing and wounding 14,645 soldiers and capturing 12,975, including
a general. Rebel claims often are exaggerated and there was no way
to verify Kidane's statement.
   Early last year, Tigrean and Eritrean rebels in a joint offensive
captured several towns, which the government retook in a midyear
counteroffensive.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for independence since 1962 in
Africa's oldest civil war. The Tigreans took up arms to demand more
autonomy.
   Mengistu inherited the rebellion in 1974 when he and fellow
officers overthrew the late Emperor Haile Selassie and established a
Marxist government.
</TEXT>
