<FIRST>r a AM-PoliceLayoffs     03-03 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Police Layoffs,0406</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Raises Money, Police Officers Recalled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MCKEESPORT, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-one laid-off police officers are
being called back to work because a drive by residents, churches and
businesses raised more than the $90,000 needed to pay them, the
mayor of this strapped steel town said Friday.
   ``I'm overwhelmed by how the people opened up their hearts and
pocketbooks,'' said Mayor Lou Washowich. ``We're a struggling
community trying to make some type of economic recovery.''
   Organizers of the drive to collect $90,000 said the total reached
$94,000 by noon Friday.
   Washowich said the officers, nearly half the force, would return
to work Sunday, one week after being laid off.
   ``This past week, while it's been very busy, the good Lord must
have been watching us because we didn't have anything terrible
happen,'' Police Chief Thomas Brletic said.
   The mayor had asked all employees to take a wage freeze after the
city discovered a $1.3 million deficit late last year, and he had
said layoffs would result if the request was refused.
   Washowich ordered the police layoffs after a panel of state
arbitrators awarded the police department 4 percent to 4{ percent
pay raises. He said the city would save $90,000 by laying off the 21
officers for three months. Twenty-nine officers remained on the job.
   The city's volunteer ambulance company, McKeesport Emergency
Medical Services, launched the fund-raising drive with a $15,000
donation.
   Residents dropped money into cans at churches, clubs, restaurants
and businesses, and the ambulance company recorded the fund total
each day on a cardboard thermometer posted at its station.
   The money includes the contributions of Equibank, which agreed to
match every donation dollar for dollar.
   ``From the beginning I thought we would get the money, but I'm
surprised we got it this quick,'' said Brian Gregg, recording
secretary of the ambulance company.
   Funeral home owner Felix Jaworski donated $200.
   ``I just want to help our police force,'' he said. ``They do a
lot for me here. We have a lot of vandalism around here and all I do
is give them a call and they're on their way.''
   Washowich said the success of the fundraiser won't solve the
city's money problems and he has no idea how McKeesport will pay for
the next year's police wage increase.
   ``I'm sorry to say the reality will set in,'' he said.
</TEXT>
