<DOCNO> AP890303-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Goetz     03-03 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Goetz,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bernhard Goetz Denied Parole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A parole board denied early release Friday to
Bernhard Goetz, who is serving a one-year jail sentence for
illegally possessing the gun he used to shoot four teen-agers on a
New York City subway in 1984.
   A short statement by the state Board of Parole said releasing
Goetz after just two months ``would deprecate the seriousness of the
crime and undermine respect for the law.''
   Edward Elwin, executive director of the parole board, said the
decision means Goetz has to serve his full sentence minus any time
off for good behavior, unless he gets a court to overturn the
board's ruling.
   Goetz could have been released Monday if the board had ruled the
other way, said Elwin.
   Goetz is ``angry. He's frustrated,'' said his lawyer, Mark Baker.
``He doesn't belong there.''
   ``It's probably one of the most political decisions that's ever
come down the pike,'' Baker said. ``Anybody in power is afraid to do
something that favors Bernhard Goetz for fear of being labeled a
racist by the fringe elements. So he sits and rots.''
   Baker said the decision might be appealed.
   Goetz, 41, was convicted on the gun charge, but acquitted of
attempted murder, assault and reckless endangerment charges. The
case drew international attention. Some people called the white
radio technician a racist vigilante for shooting four black young
men who were merely panhandling. Supporters hailed Goetz as a hero
who resisted a robbery.
   In turning Goetz down for parole, the board noted that Goetz had
fired his gun repeatedly.
   ``It is clear from the record that the present one-year sentence
for this Class-D felony, which can have a maximum sentence of seven
years, was imposed after careful and thoughtful consideration of the
circumstances of the case and the subject's background,'' said the
board's statement.
   Goetz began serving his sentence Jan. 13 after appeals in the
state courts failed to reverse his conviction. On Monday, the U.S.
Supreme Court also refused to reverse it.
   Had Goetz not appealed his conviction, he probably would have
ended up serving considerably less time in jail. While upholding the
conviction, state appeals courts also ruled that Goetz had been
sentenced incorrectly. The trial judge had given him six months. At
his court-ordered re-sentencing, Goetz was given the one-year term.
   Goetz is serving his sentence in New York City's Rikers Island
jail, where he has been repairing radios for the police and fire
departments.
   Elwin said Goetz got the standard treatment the parole board
gives city jail inmates. One member, whom he would not identify,
reviewed the prisoner's record and letters sent in by the judge,
prosecutor and defense lawyers, Elwin said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-MinimumWage     03-03 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minimum Wage,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Minimum Backed, But With Lower `Training Wage'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole told Congress on
Friday that President Bush will veto any attempt to raise the
minimum wage beyond the administration's goal of $4.25 an hour at
the end of three years, and unless the legislation includes a
``training wage'' for all newly hired workers.
   Mrs. Dole's blunt warning came as she formally presented the plan
to the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee, setting the
administration strongly against a plan by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., and majority Democrats that would raise the hourly minimum
to $4.65.
   She contended the Democratic plan, similar to one that died under
opposition by then-President Reagan last year, would cost 650,000
jobs.
   Bush's plan would raise the $3.35 minimum wage, unchanged since
1981, by 30 cents an hour a year until it reaches $4.25 an hour in
1991. All new workers hired at the minimum could be paid $3.35 an
hour for the first six months of their employment.
   ``Any more expansive approach at this time would be unacceptable
because it would decrease job opportunities,'' Mrs. Dole said.
``Legislation outside these parameters would call for a veto.''
   Kennedy told Mrs. Dole he hoped that ``we're not getting hit with
a take it or leave it.''
   Mrs. Dole said bluntly, ``The president has signed up for $4.25
an hour. and not higher.
   ``$4.25 is it,'' she said, waving her hand.
   The Labor committee will consider the bill Kennedy introduced
with Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, who has said he wants a
floor debate and vote on the question by the end of the month.
   Under the ``training wage,'' all workers hired at the minimum
could be paid $3.35 an hour for six months before they are covered
by the higher standard. Kennedy and other key Democrats and
organized labor have opposed setting a lower standard for any
workers, which organized labor fears could cause companies to layoff
higher-paid workers in favor of those who can be paid less.
   Twelve states and the District of Columbia have raised the
minimum wage in laws that take precedence over the federal standard
inside their borders, according to the Labor Department. California
and Connecticut have the highest minimum at $4.25 an hour, although
D.C. has a $4.85 floor for some workers.
   The other states with minimums higher than the federal government
are Alaska, Hawaii, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Hampshire,
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1608EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-India     03-03 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gandhi Proposes Political Package To End Sikh Turmoil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi announced
political initiatives Friday to help heal the ethnic rift with
rebellious Sikhs in the prosperous farming state of Punjab, news
reports said.
   Gandhi said he will free most people detained in the 1984 army
raid on the Golden Temple in Amritsar; rescind legislation allowing
detention without trial; and allow foreigners to travel around most
of northwestern Punjab state.
   Opposition and ruling party legislators, including some who
support Sikh militants, loudly thumped their desks in a traditional
expression of approval when Gandhi announced the initiatives in
Parliament, United News of India agency said.
   Gandhi gave no time frame for the measures, Indian TV said.
   ``This is a step in the right direction. It is better late than
never,'' said Sikhdev Singh Dhindsa, a former Punjab state transport
minister and member of the United Akali Dal, a Sikh party
sympathetic to Sikh militants.
   Dhindsa told The Associated Press the measures would help solve
ethnic strife that began in 1982 when Sikh militants began a bloody
insurrection in demand of an independent homeland in Punjab.
   Referring to the release of the Jodhpur detenus, so called
because most were detained in Jodhpur jail in Rajasthan state after
the temple raid, Dhindsa said ``other innocent people in Punjab
jails should also be released.''
   Some 300 people were arrested in the Golden Temple complex during
the 1984 army raid ordered by Gandhi's mother, assassinated Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi.
   Most were pilgrims held for questioning for complicity with Sikh
militants who were holed up inside the temple complex. About 150
still are detained, many without charge.
   Gandhi said all except those who face specific criminal charges
will be released soon, UNI said.
   Foreigners will be permitted regular access to Punjab and barred
only from areas declared severely ``disturbed'' or overrun by
militants, UNI quoted Gandhi as saying. Presently, all foreigners
except accredited journalists need special permission to visit
Punjab.
   Gandhi also said he will rescind special provisions of the
National Security Act allowing people in Punjab to be detained
without charge for six months, UNI said.
   He told legislators the government also will curtail emergency
powers given police under the Terrorist and Disruptive Activities
Act, the news agency said.
   Village defense forces will be revived, Gandhi said, so people
rely less on police for help against militants.
   Village-level elections will be held between May and September,
Gandhi said, and committees based on the elections will supervise
development work and law and order.
   Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of India's population, but
they are in a slight majority in Punjab, India's agricultural boom
state.
   Militant Sikhs claim they are discriminated against by a
government dominated by the overwhelming Hindu majority, who are 82
percent of India's 880 million people.
   Militants wield enormous clout on the plea they are defending the
Sikh religion from being swamped by Hinduism.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed by two Sikh bodyguards to avenge
the assault on the temple that is Sikhism's most holy place.
   In 1988, the militants killed 2,400 people, mostly Hindus and
moderate Sikhs opposed to their campaign for a separate homeland.
   Punjab state legislature is suspended and the state is under
President's Rule, administered directly by New Delhi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0097 </DOCNO>
