<FIRST>u w AM-BudgetTalks Bjt   03-03 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Budget Talks, Bjt,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brady, Darman Meet Congressional Leaders to Discuss Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady and White
House Budget Director Richard Darman met with congressional leaders
Friday in a renewed effort to open negotiations on President Bush's
$1.16 trillion spending plan.
   After the two hours of closed-door talks, Democratic leaders
indicated that they believed serious discussions would begin perhaps
as soon as next week.
   Since Bush unveiled his budget on Feb. 9, he has been pushing to
start bargaining talks with Congress on a 1990 spending plan in
order to assure financial markets that progress is being made in
reducing the budget deficit, which is expected to hit $170 billion
this year.
   Congressional Democrats had refused to say whether they would be
willing to bargain with the administration, insisting instead that
Bush needed to spell out in greater detail the spending cuts he
would seek in order to reduce the 1990 deficit below $100 billion.
   While Darman has been meeting for the past three weeks with
members of the budget committees, those sessions have been described
as fact-finding talks in which the Democrats were searching for the
fine print in the Bush budget.
   Democrats have been insisting that the administration spell out
some $10 billion in unspecified savings Bush is seeking in scores of
domestic programs in order to meet his deficit reduction goals.
   Democrats have complained that Bush has wanted to take credit for
boosting spending in such areas as education and the war on drugs
while making the Democratic-controlled Congress take the blame for
cutting programs or boosting taxes to pay for Bush's increases.
   On Friday, House Budget Committee Chairman Leon Panetta,
D-Calif., said he believed the fact-finding phase of the discussions
was essentially at an end and it would now be up to Democratic
leaders in Congress to decide whether to authorize direct
negotiations with the administration.
   Panetta characterized Friday's discussions as a talk about what
format the actual bargaining should take and who should participate.
   ``It would be fair to say that there is some movement toward
beginning negotiations with the administration,'' Senate Budget
Committee Chairman James Sasser, D-Tenn., told reporters after the
meeting.
   ``We have still got some hoops to go through before we get into
negotiations, but I am hopeful,'' Sasser said.
   Both Sasser and Panetta stressed that they viewed the effort to
draft a 1990 budget as a two-track process involving both the normal
congressional committee hearings and the negotiations with the
administration.
   ``In the event that these negotiations are unsuccessful, then we
could carry on with the budget process and hit our targets (for
completing work on a budget) as required by statute,'' Sasser said.
   April 15 is the deadline for Congress to produce an initial
budget resolution establishing broad spending guidelines for the
1990 fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
   Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, ranking Republican on the
Senate Budget Committee, said that ``time is running out so some
decisions will have to be made.'' He said various options had been
explored but no final decisions were made at the Friday meeting.
   Darman and Brady walked past reporters without pausing to answer
questions. While Darman has been meeting on a regular basis with
ranking Democrats and Republicans on the House and Senate budget
committees, it was the first time that Brady had gone to the Capitol
to participate in the talks.
   Darman last week predicted in a meeting with reporters that
serious talks would begin within two weeks, in part because the
Democrats would realize that the sessions would prove to be to their
benefit.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., who also
participated in the discussions Friday, said: ``We are nearing the
end of one phase of the discussions and looking at the next step.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
