<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Cooper     03-03 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cooper,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italians Deliver 1 Million Petitions to U.N. on Behalf of Condemned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group opposed to the death penalty said
Friday it gave U.N. officials petitions with more than 1 million
signatures denouncing such punishment and asking clemency for a
woman on death row in Indiana.
   The Indiana Supreme Court is considering an appeal of the murder
conviction of Paula Cooper, 19, who is held at the Indiana Women's
Prison in Indianapolis.
   Ms. Cooper was 15 in 1985 when she and three other teen-agers
from Gary, Ind., robbed and killed Ruth Elizabeth Pelke, a
78-year-old retired Bible teacher. Ms. Pelke was stabbed at least 30
times with a butcher knife.
   ``Thou Shalt Not Kill,'' an Italian anti-death penalty group,
presented petitions with more than 1 million signatures appealing
for mercy for Ms. Cooper to U.N. officials.
   Members of the group say they have also sent more than 2 million
signatures gathered throughout Europe to Indiana officials,
including an appeal Pope John Paul II issued in 1987.
   The United Nations does not issue appeals for clemency in death
penalty cases unless they involve political crimes or violations of
human rights. The Italians conceded Ms. Cooper's case did not fit
those categories.
   Roman Catholics and some leftist groups in Europe have adopted
Ms. Cooper as the figurehead of their campaign against capital
punishment. Amnesty International and the American Civil Liberties
Union also have called for mercy.
   ``We're talking about a girl in the flower of her youth, in the
prime of life,'' said Don Germano Greganti, the president of ``Thou
Shalt Not Kill.''
   ``In a sense, it's the defense of the ultimate person _ an
adolescent, someone who needs the support of family and the
political structure to complete her growth,'' said Greganti.
   Greganti also noted that Ms. Cooper is black, ``and black people
have been subject to a great deal of intolerence and
discrimination.''
   ``She has murdered someone,'' said Paolo Pietrosanti, another
member of the group, ``but we also say that the most vile homicide
is that which is perpetrated and premeditated by the largest number
of people.
   ``This premeditated homicide itself is the death penalty,''
Pietrosanti said.
   Members of ``Thou Shalt Not Kill'' met with Cooper for three
hours in her Indiana prison cell this week.
   When Ms. Cooper was sentenced, Indiana law allowed the death
penalty for anyone over the age of 10 convicted of murder. The age
limit has since been raised to 16, but was not made retroactive.
   As of Feb. 1, 27 people awaited execution in the United States
for crimes they committed before reaching age 18. Ms. Cooper and
Troy Dugar of Louisiana are the only condemned prisoners who
committed their crimes before age 16.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
