<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MinorityParticipation     03-03 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minority Participation,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Atlanta Mayor Says No Moratorium On Building Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Andrew Young ruled out halting new city
building projects Friday in reaction to a Georgia Supreme Court
ruling that voided Atlanta's program to encourage minority-owned
contractors.
   ``We will do what we have to do on a case-by-case basis without
minority regulation,'' Young said. ``I hope we can continue to do
business together.''
   Young, a longtime civil rights leader, cited decades of slavery
and segregation in likening the stricken Atlanta plan to the
Marshall Plan that helped Europe back to its feet after World War II.
   ``We can't help but begin to see that the Reagan legacy has come
home to roost,'' Young said.
   He said the Atlanta program, which set a goal of 35 percent
minority participation in city contracts, had been aimed at ``full
participation'' by all sectors of Atlanta.
   Young said at a news conference there was no need for a
moratorium on contracts because most of the major projects he had
planned in his nearly eight years in office already are under way.
   The Georgia Supreme Court ruled 7-0 Thursday that Atlanta's
Minority-Female Business Enterprise program was unconstitutional and
that the city's defense of the 14-year-old program was ``woefully
inadequate.'' It said there was insufficient evidence of past
discrimination.
   Young said Friday that the guidelines were drawn and implemented
``in the implicit spirit of fairness'' to Atlanta's black majority.
   Young said there would be no appeal to federal courts, but the
city might seek clarifications or modifications at the state level.
   Thursday's ruling followed the U.S. Supreme Court decision in
January to overturn a set-aside program in Richmond, Va.
   ``We never had quotas, we never had set-asides. We simply had
goals,'' Young said. ``We had a flexible approach we felt was quite
different from Richmond.''
   Last year, Atlanta awarded $29.4 million to minority-owned and
operated companies, 36.7 percent of all city contracting business.
More than $300 million in city business has gone to minority
companies since the 35 percent minority participation goal was
established in 1975.
   The court found that the program was too broadly drawn and that
the city failed to consider alternatives to a yearly minority
participation goal in its contracting.
   In overturning an earlier Superior Court ruling that upheld the
program, the Supreme Court indicated that Atlanta could have used
milder measures in its affirmative action efforts but did not fully
explore them.
   The high court's ruling was on behalf of the American
Subcontractors Association, whose attorney, J. Ben Shapiro, praised
the court's decision.
   ``That program is illegal as of right now,'' Shapiro said.
   It was not immediately clear whether the ruling effectively
dismantles the program. Young said city experts needed time to study
the ruling.
   Some city business leaders expressed optimism that Atlanta's
biracial business climate would survive the ruling.
   ``The program allowed us to develop certain relationships,'' said
Tom Cordy, president of AMC Mechanical Contractors, one of the
partners in the construction of the Underground Atlanta
entertainment complex. ``Those relationships will go on. People will
continue to do business as we have.''
   Fulton and DeKalb counties, which include parts of Atlanta, have
goals of 20 percent minority participation in county contracts.
Their programs were not affected by the ruling Thursday, but the
Fulton County program is being challenged in federal court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
