<FIRST>r i AM-Andropov     03-03 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Andropov,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Named For Andropov Gets Back Original Name</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party officials removed Yuri V.
Andropov's name from a city north of Moscow, Tass said Friday,
making him the latest former leader whose name has been wiped off
Soviet maps.
   Residents of the city 150 miles north of the capital had asked
that Rybinsk assume its original name, the official news agency said.
   A Soviet atlas published in 1986 lists the city by the name of
Rybinsk, with ``Andropov'' in parenthesis.
   Andropov headed the KGB until Leonid I. Brezhnev died in 1982,
when he became Kremlin leader. He was a mentor of President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev until his death in 1984, when he was succeeded by
Konstantin U. Chernenko.
   Tass said the Communist Party Central Committee, the Supreme
Soviet Presidium and the Soviet government reversed their 1984
decision naming the city after Andropov.
   Andropov has not been widely attacked in the official media under
Gorbachev.
   In January 1988, a city, squares and a Moscow neighborhood were
stripped of the name Brezhnev, who is now blamed for stagnation and
bloated bureaucracy.
   In December, Kremlin officials ordered the names of Brezhnev and
Chernenko wiped off their homes and any other towns, schools or
factories that still bore their name.
   Associates of former Soviet leader Josef Stalin also have had
their names removed from cities and squares.
   Western diplomats disagreed about whether there is any
significance to the move in a society where place names are being
changed because of political disgrace and also to reinstate more
popular, historic names eliminated without the approval of residents.
   ``It's a major change in the leadership's approach to Andropov,''
said a high-ranking Western diplomat who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``This is the first concrete indication'' that Gorbachev is in
``political trouble'' because he was Andropov's protege, he said.
But he also said the name change also may be part of Gorbachev's
rejection of a cult of personality for former leaders.
   Another Moscow-based Western diplomat said the change could be
part of a general move in the Soviet Union to give back cities their
traditional names. ``I'm surprised if it is a criticism of Andropov
_ it seems rather odd,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
