<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     03-03 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Army Reinforces Troops in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ZAHRANI, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of Lebanon's Moslem army
units sent about 500 soldiers and 10 aging Soviet-designed tanks
Friday to south Lebanon, where he has said he expects ``an Israeli
operation at any time.''
   The 3,000 Lebanese soldiers already in the south are not equipped
with tanks. they have stayed out of Israel's fight with Palestinian
and Shiite Moslem guerrillas in the area.
   Israel maintains a ``security zone'' just inside Lebanon with the
aid of a predominantly Christian surrogate militia. Its military
command refused comment Friday on the Lebanese troop movements, but
a spokesman said the ``army is doing everything to secure its
northern border.''
   Two Israeli jet fighters flew reconnaissance as the mechanized
battalion moved to Zahrani, 35 miles south of Beirut. Palestinian
and Lebanese militia gunners fired at them but no hits were reported.
   Maj. Gen. Sami Khatib, who commands the Moslem units of the
divided Lebanese army, said in an interview this week he would send
reinforcements south to fight Israel and cooperate with U.N.
peacekeeping troops in the area.
   He said he expected an Israeli operation soon and ``we'll fight
and try to hamper the enemy's advance as much as we can.''
   The soldiers who arrived Friday deployed around the Zahrani oil
refinery, but a Lebanese military spokesman said they and their T-54
tanks would move to Zaghdraya. The inland town, 12 miles from the
Israeli zone, is the army's most forward position in south Lebanon.
   Khatib said Lebanese soldiers would help the U.N. Interim Force
in Lebanon enforce Security Council Resolution 425. The resolution,
passed after an Israeli invasion in 1978, calls for the
unconditional withdrawal of Israeli forces and deployment of the
5,800-member force along the border.
   UNIFIL, whose area of operations overlaps the buffer zone, has
not been able to move to the border because the Israelis will not
pull back.
   Israel invaded Lebanon again in June 1982 and established the
security zone after withdrawing most of its troops three years later.
   Lebanese soldiers have been caught in crossfire several times but
have not fought a major engagement with Israeli for more than 16
years. The army did not confront the Israelis in either invasion.
   Khatib commands 22,000 soldiers based in Moslem territory south
of Beirut and along the coast, and Gen. Michel Aoun has 20,000
Christian troopers in the Christian area north and east of the
capital.
   The army divided when Moslem militias drove Christian units from
Moslem west Beirut in February 1984, nine years after Lebanon's
sectarian civil war began. Aoun technically commanded the entire
army, however, until a deadlock on the presidential succession
created two governments last fall.
   President Amin Gemayel's six-year term ended with no successor
elected because right-wing Christians opposed candidates chosen by
neighboring Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon.
   Christian and Moslem governments emerged from the crisis, with
the Christian cabinet led by Aoun, a fellow Maronite Catholic chosen
by Gemayel as caretaker prime minister.
   Moslems would not accept Aoun's authority and acting Premier
Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who heads the Moslem cabinet, named
Khatib commander of Moslem army units.
   By longstanding agreement, Lebanon's president is Christian, the
premier Sunni and the Parliament speaker Shiite Moslem.
   Syria, which has 40,000 soldiers in Lebanon, supports Khatib's
command.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
