<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Army     03-03 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Army,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Army Trains Special Motorized Anti-Uprising Units</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army is training special units to deal
exclusively with the Palestinian uprising so that other soldiers can
perform duties elsewhere, the army weekly Bamahane reported in its
latest issue.
   The troops will undergo basic infantry training, followed by
training on armored personnel carriers. They will then take a new
anti-uprising course, the newspaper said.
   If a war broke out, the units would serve as mechanized infantry,
Bamahane said.
   ``Their year will consist of nine months of security duty in the
territories and three months of mechanized infantry training,'' Col.
M, personnel chief of the army's ground forces, was quoted as saying.
   His full name was not released, in keeping with military
regulations.
   Senior army officials have complained that dealing with the
15-month uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip has
severely affected the army's training program.
   Many reserve and regular units, instead of training, have been
sent to patrol the occupied territories.
   In addition, the United States alleged last month that Israel's
failure to train professional riot control forces led to an increase
in casualties.
   When the revolt broke out Dec. 8, 1987, soldiers were sent to
deal with stone-throwing demonstrators without helmets, clubs or
sufficient amounts of tear gas.
   Many of the Arab deaths have since been blamed on army reservists
or teen-age recruits inexperienced in civilian riot control. In the
last 15 months, at least 388 Palestinians have been killed.
   During the same time frame, Israeli media say professional police
forces such as the Border Police have not killed a single
Palestinian.
   The new ``Allon units'' _ apparently named ofter Yigal Allon, a
founder of pre-state elite commando units _ came under attack from
both ends of the political spectrum.
   ``Maybe it will bring the casualties down, but the uprising will
not stop,'' said Ran Cohen, a reserve colonel and a legislator of
the leftist Citizens Rights Movement. ``This is part of a very
dangerous process of turning the army and its troops into a colonial
police force.''
   Rafael Eitan, a right-wing Parliament member and former army
chief of staff, called the idea of special units ``rubbish.''
   ``You don't need special units, you have to know how to punish,''
he said.
   ``They think that by changing organization they'll solve the
problem,'' Eitan continued. ``Instead of shooting children, we
should expel their leaders and give missions to the Jewish
settlers.''
</TEXT>
