<FIRST>r a AM-`Today'Flap     03-03 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-`Today' Flap,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gumbel's Grumble: Scott Ponders Leaving, Pauley Says `Lighten Up'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weatherman Willard Scott says maybe he should
leave the ``Today'' show if he can't reconcile with Bryant Gumbel
over a memo outlining Gumbel's blunt complaints about Scott and
other on-air personalities.
   Gumbel's co-host, Jane Pauley, who wasn't mentioned in the memo,
has suggested that everybody ``lighten up.''
   Earlier this week, New York Newsday featured a front-page story
of the leaked memo, written last August by Gumbel to ``Today''
executive producer Marty Ryan and apparently extracted from Gumbel's
computer file.
   Gumbel complained about Scott, movie reviewer Gene Shalit and
consumer advocate David Horowitz, among others.
   ``This is not a national crisis,'' Pauley told ``Entertainment
Tonight'' in an interview for broadcast Friday night. ``Sure it was
a problem, but every family has it's ups and downs.''
   Gumbel's most critical comments were aimed at Scott for his
alleged ``bad taste.'' ``This guy is killing us,'' Gumbel grumbled.
Gumbel complained that Scott used valuable time on the morning NBC
news show to display T-shirts, souvenirs and photos of elderly
birthday celebrants.
   Gumbel has been on vacation and has not commented on the memo.
   ``If it's not real, and if there isn't an honest, genuine
reconciliation, I don't think I belong there,'' Scott said on
Thursday night's ``Entertainment Tonight.'' Scott and Gumbel won't
be on the set together for at least a week, because Scott is on
vacation next week.
   ``My whole act hangs on working the neighborhood, you know, doing
the T-shirts and plugging the birthdays _ I wasn't aware that he was
unhappy with that,'' Scott said.
   NBC News President Michael Gartner said in a memorandum to staff
members that if he finds who leaked the memo, the person will be
fired.
</TEXT>
