<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--SeizedEngravings     03-03 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Seized Engravings,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Charged With Illegal Export of Engravings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOMODOSSOLA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American has been charged by Italian
customs police with trying to export ancient engravings and a fossil
illegally, authorities said Friday.
   Dr. Russell Lewis Coulson of Peoria, Ill., did not try to hide
the objects when he was checked by Italian border police on a train
to Geneva, said police Lt. Col. Umberto Selvaggi.
   ``He did not know that the objects were subject to artistic
protection and could not be taken abroad,'' Selvaggi said.
   Police said the 46-year-old dentist bought the fish fossil and
six engravings dating back to the 15th and 17th centuries in Venice.
Authorities said they did not know the value of the objects.
   Coulson, who was stopped Feb. 25, was charged with trying to
export objects subject to artistic protection, a crime that carries
a maximum penalty of four months in jail and a fine based on the
value of the objects.
   He was allowed to continue his journey and return to the United
States.
</TEXT>
