<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Mayors     03-03 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Mayors,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Half of Towns Without Mayors Because of Guerrilla Threats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Half the country's 262 towns and
cities were without mayors Friday, the result of a terror campaign
by revolutionaries who say municipal chiefs administer U.S. designs.
   ``Fear is human,'' said Armando Calderon Sol, mayor of San
Salvador, in a recent interview with The Associated Press.
   ``They (other mayors) come to me for advice, but I can't ask them
to be cannon fodder. They have their families to think about. I tell
them it's a personal choice.''
   The Interior Ministry says 131 mayors have chosen to resign.
   Some have been replaced by low-profile ``substitutes'' _ usually
a member of the municipal council.
   Most have simply locked their doors, leaving residents no means
of locally registering births and deaths, getting married or
complaining about potholes.
   Marxist-led revolutionaries say mayors are a principal component
of the ``U.S.-imposed counterinsurgency campaign.'' A 9-year-old
civil war has killed an estimated 70,000 people.
   El Salvador, a nation of 5 million, is the Western Hemisphere's
biggest recipient of U.S. economic and military aid _ about $1.5
million per day. The rebels say Washington and El Salvador's ruling
class have sought, through elections, to put a democratic veneer on
a state that remains dominated by the military.
   A big chunk of U.S. aid goes to development projects administered
by the Salvadoran government through local authorities.
   Following municipal elections a year ago, the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front, or FMLN, began threatening mayors and
insisting they announce their resignations.
   The guerrillas have assassinated nine mayors. The most recent
slaying was in the eastern town of Sesori on Nov. 24. During the
last two months of 1988, several municipal chiefs a week were taking
to the air waves and buying newspaper ads to announce their
resignations.
   At first, the guerrillas concentrated on their ``zones of
control'' _ the northern sectors of Chalatenango, Morazan, San
Miguel and Cabanab provinces where they move freely and enjoy
considerable support. But by late last year they were threatening
mayors nationwide.
   Mayor Ricardo de Leon of San Miguel, the nation's third-largest
city, remains in his post despite two threats last month.
   ``I'm not challenging the insurgents to kill me,'' de Leon, of
the rightist Republican National Alliance, said in an interview.
   ``I don't have enemies. I don't even consider the left my enemy,
because serving the people includes serving the left. But the people
gave me this post, and only the people can tell me to leave it,'' he
said.
   De Leon asked the Roman Catholic Church to arrange a meeting with
local guerrilla leaders so he could ask them ``why I am considered a
military target.''
   He's still waiting to be contacted.
   ``Of course I'm afraid. But the support of the people gives me
valor,'' he said.
   The campaign has been condemned by the Christian Democratic
government, the armed forces, and even the Democratic Convergence, a
guerrilla-allied leftist electoral front.
   The rebels, as part of a peace proposal, offered to stop the
campaign if the government postponed presidential elections
scheduled March 19 and met their demands for security and anti-fraud
measures during the vote.
   The government and rebels have not been able to agree on when,
where or how to negotiate on the proposal, which also ecompasses
many other issues.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2339EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MarineRecruiting     03-03 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marine Recruiting,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Recruiting Irregularities Lead Marines To Tell 135 Recruits To Forget
It</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marines have told 135 young people who
signed up for the Corps but were not slated to report until later
not to bother showing up, because their recruitments were fraudulent
and they really weren't qualified, a spokesman said.
   Word of their release from the Corps' delayed-entry program
follows the dismissal of 30 recruits last month from boot camp at
Parris Island, S.C.
   All the dismissals stem from the discovery that high school
diplomas were fabricated and criminal and medical records were
disregarded by the Pittsburgh recruiting station, said Corps
spokesman Maj. Robert W. McLean at Parris Island. Investigators
concluded that recruiters signed up young men who weren't qualified
in order to meet their recruitment quotas.
   Records of an additional 20 recruits in the delayed-entry program
are being reviewed, he said Friday.
   McLean said earlier this week that Maj. George A. Eberhart Jr.,
head of the Pittsburgh recruiting station, and 15 of his recruiters
were relieved of duty and that two additional recruiters received
administrative warnings because of the improper recruiting. In all,
there are 47 recruiters assigned to Pittsburgh.
   None of the young men sent home from boot camp or released from
the delayed-entry program faces any disciplinary charges, officials
said.
   The actions follow an investigation triggered by a suburban
Pittsburgh recruit's claim that his recruiter enlisted him even
though he knew the young man had a severe stomach ulcer that should
have disqualified him. The recruit had to be hospitalized while at
boot camp.
   McLean said 30 recruits were sent home from boot camp after a
review of 83 questionable cases. He told The Press on Thursday that
in addition, 135 of nearly 700 recruits in the Corps'
delayed-enlistment program were also released ``over the same
reasons that the others were disqualified for.''
   The delayed-enlistment program allows recruits to commit
themselves to the Corps without reporting to boot camp until up to
six months later.
   Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa., said he met with the Marine Corps'
congressional liaison and was told the Marines ``have never
experienced this widespread a problem in their memory'' with
fabricated recruitments.
   ``This is a very high number of recruiters in a relatively small
pool for them all to be involved in what is clearly a serious
violation of rules,'' Walgren said. ``That number suggests they are
under extraordinary pressure to produce, or it's something far
widespread beyond this recruiting station.''
   The head of the Army recruiting battalion in Pittsburgh said
Thursday that a surprise inspection in November found six instances
of possible improper recruiting. Four recruits were recommended for
dismissal and two cases have not been resolved, said Col. Randell
Wilkes.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
