<FIRST>u i PM-Venezuela 5thLd-Writethru   03-03 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Venezuela, 5th Ld - Writethru,a0558,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perez Says Venezuela Has Suspended All Debt Payments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to CORRECT that Perez not suspending debt payment
but saying whether debt payments can be made depends on austerity program;
no pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY4,NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIA TEJERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Andres Perez today
said whether Venezuela can continue to make payments on its foreign
debt depends on the success of its austerity program.
   ``The crisis Latin American nations are undergoing has a name
written with capital letters _ foreign debt,'' Perez told foreign
correspondents at Miraflores Palace, the government headquarters.
   A newspaper today reported more than 300 people died and and
1,500 were injured since Monday in riots in Caracas and 11 other
cities. The unrest was caused by government-imposed bus fare
increases, which appeared to release pent up frustration over the
nation's austerity program.
   Buses and cars circulated in Caracas today as the capital
returned to normal, with early morning traffic jams and honking
horns replacing some of the tensions of this week's unrest.
   Looters emptied the shelves of supermarkets and neighborhood
grocery stores in the first days of rioting. Since then, part of the
22,000 police and soldiers ordered on alert in Caracas have guarded
stores, where people have been waiting hours in line to buy such
staples as eggs, bread and cheese.
   Perez, in a morning news conference, said payments on the
country's $33 million foreign debt depends on ``how our economic
program develops.''
   Venezuela, affluent during the 1970s thanks to its rich oil
reserves, saw its fortunes slide along with petroleum prices in 1981.
   Real wages have since then fallen by a third, inflation is
expected to double this year to 70 percent, and the $33 billion
foreign debt is the fourth largest in Latin America after Brazil,
Mexico and Argentina.
   Venezuela suspended payments on $20.4 billion of the debt in
January, and the newspaper El Nacional reported last week that
payments on another $5 billion of the debt was suspended.
   Earlier this week, the government asked the International
Monetary Fund to include provisions allowing Venezuela to suspend
all payments on its debt until September. Venezuela also asked for
an additional $4.3 billion in loans from the institution over the
next three years.
   Asked if he intended to delay repayment beyond September, Perez
said it would depend on the success of his economic adjustment
program.
   Perez, who has been in office for only one month, has blamed
leftists for prolonging Venezuela's worst unrest in 31 years of
democratic rule.
   On Wednesday, Gabriel Puerta, a former guerrilla leader, accused
the government of inventing political motives for the disturbances,
which he blamed on the failure of the government's economic policies.
   On Thursday evening, soldiers hunting snipers and seeking looters
conducted house-to-house searches in downtown Caracas and the
western slums. Shooting was heard early today as soldiers fired into
the air and at buildings to flush out snipers. It appeared the
gunfire also was meant to enforce the government's dusk-to-dawn
curfew by keeping people off the streets.
   El Nacional said in today's edition that more than 300 people had
been killed and 1,500 injured in four days of violence _ the
bloodiest in Venezuela's history. Other reports said the death toll
ranged from 250 to 350.
   The newspaper said its reporters counted 237 bodies at the
Caracas central morgue and said there were other bodies in hospitals
across the city. The dead included at least four children aged 3 to
14.
   Perez aide Reinaldo Figueredo said the government is setting up a
food-distribution network with supplies airlifted from the rest of
the country.
</TEXT>
