<FIRST>u a AM-UnitedPilot Bjt   03-03 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-United Pilot, Bjt,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crew Describes Saving Flight 811</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot who landed a jetliner after its
side ripped open, ejecting nine passengers, said Friday that after
the shock he said a quick prayer for his passengers and went back to
work.
   Capt. David Cronin was in charge of United Airlines Flight 811 on
its Feb. 24 non-stop flight from Honolulu to Auckland, New Zealand,
when shortly after takeoff the Boeing 747's right forward cargo door
and an adjoining 10-by-10 foot section of fuselage tore away.
   In addition to the nine people missing, 27 were injured in the
turbulence of the sudden decompression and the flight back to
Honolulu.
   Cronin said the accident outweighed anything he experienced in
the military as a fighter pilot.
   After realizing the extent of damage to the plane, ``I said a
prayer for them (passengers) momentarily and got back to business,''
Cronin said at a news conference held within earshot of jets taking
off and landing at San Francisco International Airport.
   First Officer Al Slader said simulated disaster exercises
undertaken annually by United personnel were important but
insufficient for the many problems that faced them.
   The crew ``reverted almost to survival instincts,'' Slader said.
   The crewmembers' answers were carefully controlled by airline
officials, who prohibited them from answering questions pertaining
to concerns about aging aircraft or the investigation of the
disaster.
   Cronin was on his next-to-last flight, after 38 years of military
and commercial flying and he said he's looking forward to his next _
and final _ flight.
   Because the flight took off through a fierce thunderstorm, he
said he had ordered passengers to keep their seatbelts fastened.
Without that precaution, many more lives would definitely have been
lost, Cronin said.
   After the accident, the crew members said, they reached for
oxygen masks but found the oxygen lines had been severed.
   Cronin said the plane was ``quivering and shuddering'' and he
could see flames from one wing.
   During the 25-minute flight back to Honolulu, the crew had to
dump 90,000 pounds of fuel, partly because with only two engines the
plane was, in effect, overloaded.
   In addition, the gaping hole in the side created drag which
affected speed and control.
   Part of the emergency descent procedure for getting the plane
back down to breathable air is to lower the landing gear to create
drag.
   But Cronin said their decision not to lower the landing gear
probably was critical to keeping the big jet from losing altitude
too quickly before its remaining engines got it back to the Honolulu
runway.
   If they had lowered the wheels immediately, there ``would have
been a good chance we would have gone in the water,'' he said.
   The crew also agreed to gradually move landing flaps to angles
not normally prescribed to keep the plane in the air.
   ``I don't think a 747 has ever flown on two engines at that
weight. My concern for being overweight was staying airborne,'' the
pilot told the Washington Post on Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, Second Officer Mark Thomas said he checked out the
passenger area and saw ``no panic at all'' and that none of the
passengers were moving.
   Normal landing speed with all four engines would have been 132
knots. The crew estimated that 170 knots would be safe. Cronin said
he chose to touch down at 200 knots because he was afraid of losing
control of the jet if he slowed it further.
   Once the plane reached view of Honolulu International, he said he
was confident of the plane's safe landing, which took up two-thirds
of the runway because of their speed and not having reverse thrust
from all four engines.
   ``There was a sigh of relief and we started looking after the
passengers,'' Thomas said.
   After all remaining passengers had unloaded, Cronin said he and
the other two crew members left by way of an emergency chute. They
inspected the damage, which he described as ``a hole you could drive
a semi-truck through.''
   ``My reaction was, I can't tell you what my reaction was, like
`Oh, (pause) you know what. Oh, dear.'''
</TEXT>
