<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     03-03 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Call Boycott of March 19 Presidential Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels on Friday called
for a boycott of the presidential election scheduled for March 19,
saying the vote would aggravate war and poverty.
   The insurgents have proposed postponement of the election until
September. They said if the vote were put off, they would
participate and respect its outcome.
   ``We call on the our people not to vote March 19,'' said the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front on its clandestine radio
station.
   Despite more than five weeks of debate on the guerrilla proposal,
the Christian Democratic government and the insurgents have not been
able to agree on when, where or how to negotiate its possible
implementation.
   A leftist electoral front on Friday accused the government and
the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena, of
procrastinating in response to the plan.
   Arena controls the legislature and is favored to win the
presidential election. It is adamantly opposed to postponement of
the vote.
   ``The Christian Democratic Party and Arena are trying to take
advantage of the situation for propagandistic electoral ends, thus
manipulating the people's desire for peace,'' said the leftist
Democratic Convergence.
   It alleged in a communique that the two parties intend to prevent
postponement by stalling until March 19.
   The leftist alliance proposed rescheduling the election July 9.
It also said the government, the FMLN and representatives of the
political parties should meet in Mexico next week to negotiate an
end to the 9-year-old civil war.
   ``The election of March 19 is designed to sustain the war after
the previous five flawed elections have aggravated the original
causes of the conflict,'' said the rebels on Radio Venceremos.
   ``We have proposed to compete in the political sphere, in which
clear and clean results would conciliate the parties in conflict in
light of the inviability of continuing the war,'' they said. ``But
those who have made a living from the war have sought to close the
doors to peace.''
   ``The elections of March 19 will only aggravate hunger and
misery, as they hold out no hope of real solution for the country's
crisis,'' the rebels said.
</TEXT>
