<FIRST>r w AM-Guatemala-Nicaragua     03-03 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Guatemala-Nicaragua,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cerezo: Ortega ``Doesn't Like Democracy''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo said Friday
political realities are pushing Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega
to abandon a ``totalitarian'' blueprint and pursue a democratic
outcome for his country.
   Cerezo, who is here for talks with Bush administration and
congressional leaders, said Ortega ``doesn't like democracy. He's
trying to make a revolution'' through a ``totalitarian'' formula.
   At the same time, he said, Ortega has had to pay attention to the
demands of other Central American presidents that he embrace
democracy, mindful that they would otherwise repudiate him.
   Cerezo spoke at a luncheon sponsored by the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace.
   Based on his discussions here, Cerezo said there are considerable
doubts among Bush administration officials about Ortega's
willingness to comply with the democratic promises he made at the
recent meeting of Central American presidents in El Salvador.
   Cerezo added that he believes these doubts are justified. The
administration, he said, wants more assurances that democracy will
be established in Nicaragua in a time period comparable to that of
the demobilization of the Contras.
   Still, he said, he believes the administration is convinced that
it should emphasize a diplomatic solution in Nicaragua rather than
continuing to attempt to solve problems through military force.
   Ortega spoke after administration and congressional officials
disclosed details of the ``carrot and stick'' approach to Nicaragua
advocated by Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   The policy includes unspecified rewards for Nicaragua if it
passes certain ``checkpoints'' on the road to democracy.
   Baker made clear to lawmakers that he does not intend to abandon
the Contra rebels, who now are subsisting on U.S. supplies in
Honduran jungle camps along the Nicaraguan border.
   He told congressional officials he would seek to renew the U.S.
aid, which runs out at the end of this month, for a year, according
to some present at the Thursday meetings.
   Aid would continue to flow at current rates _ about $4 million a
month _ and would keep the rebels available as a standby fighting
force until after Nicaragua's national elections, which are being
moved up to early 1990.
   At the Central American summit meeting, the five presidents
agreed to try to draft a plan that would lead to the demobilization
of the Contras in return for open elections in Nicaragua and the
release of most of the 3,300 jailed Contras and former members of
the armed forces who served under the Somoza family dynasty.
</TEXT>
