<DOCNO> AP890303-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Spy     03-03 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Spy,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Sentences Czechoslovak Spy To 10 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak spy arrested last year while
receiving secret radio messages from Prague was convicted of
espionage on Friday and sentenced to 10 years in prison.
   Erwin van Haarlem, 43, whose real identity is still not known to
police, posed as a Dutch art dealer and infiltrated Jewish groups
while sending information back to his superiors, said the
prosecution.
   It said he was an active agent here for 13 years.
   Van Haarlem pleaded innocent and was convicted by a jury after a
five-day trial at the Old Bailey Central Criminal Court.
   Judge Simon Brown recommended he be deported after serving his
sentence.
   ``I have not the least doubt that you are a dedicated,
disciplined and resourceful spy,'' Brown said.
   Van Haarlem was recording a coded message when arrested at his
north London apartment on April 2, 1988, by police from Scotland
Yard's special branch.
   Police seized six decoding guides hidden in a bar of soap,
materials for ``secret writing'' and a list of locations for
depositing and collecting material.
   Prosecutor Roy Amlot told the jury that van Haarlem received 210
coded messages from Prague after arriving in Britain in 1975.
   Among his assignments was to find out what firms were
participating in proposed ``Star Wars'' U.S. space-based defense
system, Amlot said.
   Van Haarlem joined Jewish organizations such as Conscience, a
group devoted to helping Soviet Jews, and the Women's Campaign for
Soviet Jewry.
   After his arrest, van Haarlem was taken to a police station where
he asked for a message to be relayed to the Czechoslovak Embassy:
``Erwin van Haarlem has been arrested,'' said Amlot. This was done.
   The jury was told van Haarlem adopted the name of a Dutch child
left by his mother in Prague after World War II. Amlot said the real
van Haarlem's mother searched for and found the Czechoslovak spy in
London, and he pretended he was her son. Tests determined he could
not have been her child, and she was told this. It was not clear
what happened to the real van Haarlem.
</TEXT>
