<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel     03-03 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Havel,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Proposes Havel For Nobel Peace Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia's Charter 77 human rights
movement has nominated jailed Czech playwright Vaclav Havel for the
1989 Nobel Peace Prize, an emigre source said Friday.
   The announcement came one day after 2,000 Hungarians said they
would nominate Havel for the prize during a demonstration in
Budapest seeking his freedom. Last month, two U.S. congressmen had
nominated the playwright, whose works are banned in his own country,
for the prize.
   The London-based publisher Palach Press, which monitors events in
Czechoslovakia, said a Charter 77 committee would submit the
organization's nomination to the Norwegian Nobel Committee in Oslo.
   The committee is made up of Czechoslovak activists, mainly
intellectuals, in a bid to publicize the imprisoned dramatist's case
and gain support for his nomination for the prestigious prize,
Palach Press said.
   Sen. Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz., and U.S. Rep. Steny H. Hoyer,
D-Md., also nominated Havel on Feb. 1 on behalf of the Helsinki
Commission, a human rights monitoring group.
   Havel, 52, was convicted last month on charges of incitement and
obstructing police for his role in a January rally in Prague, and he
was sentenced to nine months in jail. The January rally honored Jan
Palach, a student who set himself afire to protest the Soviet-led
invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
   Havel, who has appealed his sentence, had previously spent
slightly more than four years in jail for his rights campaign.
   A translation of the Feb. 26 letter, made available to The
Associated Press in Vienna by Palach Press, reads:
   ``We therefore believe that the Nobel Peace Prize should be
awarded primarily to those who, working outside their own profession
and often with great personal sacrifice, contribute toward making
life on this planet more just and respectable.''
   Sources linked to the Oslo committee told The Associated Press
that several proposals exist for Havel's nomination. He is one of
nearly 100 candidates, including several organizations.
   The announcement of the prize usually comes in September or
October.
</TEXT>
