<FIRST>u w AM-HowardProtest     03-03 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Howard Protest,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Take Over Auditorium Stage to Protest Choice of Atwater
as Trustee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENICE ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 students, protesting the selection
of Republican National Chairman Lee Atwater as a trustee of Howard
University, took over an auditorium stage Friday, forcing officials
to move a convocation including presentation of an honorary degree
to comedian Bill Cosby.
   Cosby was a scheduled speaker at a ceremony marking the founding
of the predominantly black university 122 years ago. But students
carrying signs demonstrated outside the auditorium, streamed inside,
chanted and took over the stage.
   Others occupied an administration building for several hours, and
some blocked reporters from entering.
   Police reported no arrests.
   The convocation was moved to an art gallery where there was a
brief ceremony to give Cosby an honorary degree before he left the
campus.
   ``The students at Howard University have a tradition of being
activists,'' university spokesman Alan Hermesch said later. ``When
they feel stongly about issues, they demonstrate.''
   University President James Cheek met with students who flocked to
a convocation luncheon, and promised to meet with several
representatives Saturday to discuss their grievances, Hermesch said.
   The students said their main complaint was the school's decision
last month to name Atwater to its board of trustees.
   Their comments indicated they identified Atwater with
controversial ads, during George Bush's presidential campaign last
year, featuring Willie Horton, a murderer who attacked a Maryland
couple while he was on furlough from a Massachusetts prison.
   The Horton issue contributed ``to the rising anti-black sentiment
of the American people,'' said Michael Lewis, a spokesman for a
group of students who organized the protest, ``and we feel that
facilitated the election of former (Ku Klux) Klansman David Duke to
the Louisiana state Legislature'' recently.
   ``We've been down this road before,'' said Mark Goodin, a
spokesman for Atwater. ``The prison furlough issue has been explored
ad nauseam,'' he said. ``That was not racially motivated whatsoever.
It was simply an issue that was explored because of the peculiarity
of the institution in Massachusetts,'' he added.
</TEXT>
