<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-03 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow Storm Moves Into Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A winter storm that had blitzed the Northwest with up to 18
inches of snow moved across the Rockies and toward the nation's
midsection Friday, dumping heavy snow on Colorado and Minnesota.
   Snowfall totals in Colorado ranged up to 16 inches at Steamboat
Lake, and in the upper Mississippi Valley, up to 9 inches of snow
blanketed southwestern Minnesota.
   Snow advisories were in effect for the mountains of Iowa, and
winter storm warnings issued for the southern and central mountains
of Colorado, the southern mountains of Wyoming, northern Iowa, and
much of Nebraska, Wisconsin and Michigan.
   Temperatures were in the single digits or below zero from the
northern half of the high Plains to upper Michigan and northern
Minnesota at midday. Strong and gusty winds in the central high
Plains were expected to cause near-blizzard conditions Friday night
and Saturday and produce wind chill readings to 40 degrees below
zero.
   Heavier snowfall totals for the six-hour period ending at 1 p.m.
EST included 5 inches at Milwaukee, 4 inches at Green Bay and 3
inches at Madison, Wis.
   Sleet and freezing rain fell from eastern Nebraska to
southwestern Michigan, changing to rain from northeast Oklahoma to
central Illinois. Rain also fell over much of the Southern Atlantic
states.
   Arctic air settled into the northwestern United States in the
wake of the snowstorm. Temperatures dipped well below freezing
across the Pacific Northwest. Astoria, Klamath Falls and Portland,
Ore., had record low temperatures for the date, with readings of 25,
10 and 19 degrees, respectively.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 9 below
zero at Cutbank, Mont., to 84 degrees at Miami and St. Petersburg,
Fla. The morning low for the nation was minus 26 at Warroad, Minn.
   Saturday's forecast called for snow from the southern and central
Rockies to the upper Great Lakes, turning to rain farther south and
east. Scattered thunderstorms were expected from the lower
Mississippi Valley to the southern Appalachians. Fair to partly
sunny skies should prevail elsewhere.
   Highs should be below freezing from the northern and central high
Plains and northwest Texas, most of Michigan and northern Maine,
dipping into the teens from Nebraska and the Dakotas to Minnesota.
Highs above 50 were forecast from western Oregon through California
and western Nevada to southern Arizona and southwestern New Mexico,
the Rio Grande Valley the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the central
Gulf Coast states, warming into the 70s and 80s in southern
California, southwestern Arizona, south-central Texas, Florida,
Georgia and South Carolina.
</TEXT>
