<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WhiteHouseReporting     03-03 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-White House Reporting,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Era in Reporting on Private Lives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of present and former White House
correspondents and former presidential press secretaries debated the
limits of reporting on private lives of public officials Friday,
with the John Tower confirmation battle as a backdrop.
   The discussion took place during a symposium on the press and the
presidency, sponsored by the National Press Foundation and the
Lyndon Baines Johnson Library.
   Eleanor Clift, who covered the White House and now covers
Congress for Newsweek, said there was an ``audible gasp'' when Tower
was asked at a Press Club luncheon earlier this week whether he had
ever violated his marriage vows.
   Tower, whose drinking habits and relations with women have
dominated debate over his nomination to be secretary of defense,
conceded he had done so, but said he didn't think he was alone.
   ``I think we all squirm a little when we get into these areas,''
Ms. Clift said. ``I think we all like to think there is a line
beyond which we personally don't go. I am uncomfortable. In the old
days there was a clear rule. If it didn't interfere with the
professional duties, it wasn't news. Well, the line between private
lives and professional duties is now so murky that almost anything
spills over. So we don't know where to draw the line.''
   Although the discussion tounched on the Tower controversy, the
question posed for the panelists was in the context of reporting
about the private lives of presidents and their families.
   James Gerstenzang of the Los Angeles Times said, ``If the
president is performing in front of us, if it's something we are
finding out, we are seeing or hearing about him, that's usable.''
   Frank Cormier, retired White House correspondent of The
Associated Press, told the group that when he was covering President
Kennedy aboard Air Force One, ``everything was off the record unless
specified otherwise.''
   ``It's very difficult for us in retrospect to realize how limited
in a sense things were 25 years ago,'' Cormier said.
   In the Johnson White House, he said, ``things got very fuzzy'' as
to what was off the record.
   ``I guess they've gotten less fuzzy now,'' he said. ``I guess
anything's fair game.''
   Marianne Means of Hearst Newspapers said reporters ``are tougher
on ourselves today in all these personal areas, as we are tougher on
our presidents.''
   Ms. Means said that when she first came to Washington, ``people
took free trips from people they were covering; the bottles of booze
would arrive at Christmas.''
   Sid Davis, a former White House correspondent for NBC News,
responded, ``It is true that journalists today don't take tickets
and booze and airplane rides, but I am not sure on the substance of
stories that the standards are better today than they were 15 or 20
years ago.''
   ``In the Kennedy era, we did hear stories about Kennedy's private
and social life, and those of us who covered Kennedy those days are
often asked why we never put those stories on the air,'' Davis said.
``The reason why we never put them on the air is because all we
heard was rumors.''
   ``There are things that happened when we were correspondents that
we didn't put on the air that would get on the air today or into
print today,'' he added.
   Larry Speakes, former spokesman for President Reagan, said
intense competition, spurred by the advent of 24-hour television,
``is driving the news to be stretched awfully thin at points.
Reporters are having to come up with some new angle on a story where
there may be no new angle.''
   Ms. Means said that the more ``packaged'' a candidate or
president become, the more ``sort of a cardboard person,'' the
greater is the pressure on reporters to ``get behind that and see
what the person is really like.''
   ``That's where we get into areas that we used to consider
strictly private,'' she said.
   Jody Powell, President Carter's press secretary, said he was
``recoiling at the thought that the packaging of the candidates
would suddenly cause us to begin writing about adultery. It seems to
me that is not exactly why we are doing it.''
   Gerald Warren, deputy press secretary to President Nixon, said,
``The press, I think all of us, must live up to a little higher
standard and I think when reports are floated around about elected
officials, both in the executive branch and on the Hill, I think we
should spend more time trying to prove or disprove those reports.''
   Helen Thomas, White House bureau chief for United Press
International, said, ``All those candidates put out a press release
every time they sneeze. They know that their life is going to be an
open book.''
</TEXT>
