<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia     03-03 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0325</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airport Assassins Kill a Top Leftist Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen killed a Marxist political leader
and one othe person during an attack Friday at Bogota's
international airport, authorities said. Eight were wounded,
including a senator.
   Police said one attacker was killed by bodyguards and three were
captured.
   Jose Antequera, an executive board member of the Marxist-oriented
Patriotic Union, was fatally shot. Officials said he was the
apparent target. He had received death threats from right-wing
paramilitary organizations here.
   Also slain was Manuel Rodriguez, an official in the Attorney
General's Office.
   Sen. Ernesto Samper Pizano of the Liberal Party, a presidential
hopeful, was wounded. Two little girls and passengers waiting to
board planes also were injured.
   The attackers used 9mm automatic handguns. They struck at 3:40
p.m., when the political leaders arrived at the airport, escorted by
bodyguards, to fly to Cucuta, near the Venezuelan border, and
Barranquilla, on the Atlantic coast.
   ``I had finished checking in my luggage to fly to Miami, when I
heard explosions and I threw myself on the floor,'' witness Carlos
Mario Velez told The Associated Press. ``I saw many people shooting
indiscriminately.''
   ``Everybody panicked,'' some another witness, who refused to give
his name. ``Some people ran and other landed on the ground and other
looked for shelter in the bathrooms and behind the airline counters.
   ``When the shooting finished, after 10 minutes, there were many
people on the ground, wounded or dead.''
   Antequera was dead on arrival at the San Pedro Claver Clinic,
said Eliana Guerra, an emergency service spokeswoman.
   Colombian paramilitary groups in the past three years have killed
more than 400 political leaders and activists belonging to Communist
and Marxist parties or affiliated with them.
   Before switching to the Patriotic Union, Antequera two years ago
was chairman of the Communist youth organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
