<FIRST>u a AM-Eastern-Schedule     03-03 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Schedule,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Cuts Weekend Schedule By 75 Percent</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said it cut its weekend schedule by
nearly 75 percent Friday but had supervisors and other workers ready
to keep the carrier operating ``indefinitely'' through a strike.
   Joseph Leonard, executive vice president and chief operating
officer, said Eastern was suspending service to nearly 60 cities on
Saturday and Sunday. Service will be maintained to almost 50 cities,
including Eastern's flights out of Miami and on its Northeast
shuttle and South American routes, Leonard said.
   The schedule changes were made as a midnight strike loomed by
Eastern's Machinists union.
   While nearly all of the more than 100 daily flights through Miami
will be maintained, Leonard said, most flights will be suspended at
Eastern's Atlanta hub.
   The company expects to gradually resume suspended flights if a
strike continued in to next week, he said. ``We do not want to
operate a schedule that is not 100 percent reliable.''
   Eastern ticket offices were extending their hours to reschedule
passengers from cancelled flights ``to the extent that is humanly
possible,'' he said.
   Eastern had strike contingency plans that would enable it to ``go
on indefinitely,'' Leonard said.
   The airline had adequate cash reserves, Leonard said, which other
sources have estimated at nearly $400 million. There were no plans
for layoffs or asset sales ``right now,'' Leonard told reporters
Friday evening.
   He said the airline would use only Eastern pilots and that there
were 200 experienced management pilots available. Although the
3,500-member pilots union planned to honor Machinists union picket
lines, Leonard predicted some union pilots would cross the picket
lines.
   Eastern's extensive strike plans also included hiring 1,100
experienced mechanics and technicians to augment management
maintenance workers, Leonard said.
   The company also has nonunion employees and supervisors ready to
fill in for flight attendants, whose 5,900-member union said it
would support the Machinists strike.
   Leonard said Eastern had actually improved its on-time
performance by 6 percent since sending the Machinists home Friday
morning to prevent sabotage. The carrier has led all major airlines
in on-time performance the past four months.
</TEXT>
