<FIRST>u a AM-PlaneCrash     03-03 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Plane Crashes Into Neighborhood, At Least One Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small plane crashed into a front yard in a
suburban neighborhood Friday, killing at least one person aboard the
plane and setting a house on fire, officials said.
   ``It looks like it hit in front of the house and cartwheeled,''
said Roanoke County Fire Chief Tommy Fuqua said. ``We've got parts
throwed from one end of the block to the other end.''
   Three people in the house escaped, said Fuqua, but no one aboard
the plane was thought to have survived.
   State police Sgt. Steve Childress said investigators believe
there was only one fatality from the plane, but said they were not
certain because the wreckage was so scattered.
   ``We've got bits and pieces of airplane and body parts. We're
trying to put everything back together,'' Childress said.
   The single-engine Cessna crashed in rainy and foggy weather, and
the cause was under investigation.
   Dallas Bryant said he, his wife, Shirley and 20-year-old
daughter, Trina, were in the house when the plane hit their yard.
``We just heard this loud explosion,'' Bryant said. ``We were in the
den and watching TV. I jumped up and hit 911.''
   Bryant said he went outside through a side door. ``The trees were
on fire and it spilled gasoline all over the yard. It was foggy.
That may have had something to do with it.''
   Childress said a Federal Aviation Administration investigation
team would arrive Saturday.
   Childress said the plane reportedly was registered in Colorado
and had taken off from an airport in northern Virginia en route to
Virginia Polytechnic Institute and State University in Blacksburg,
about 25 miles southwest of Roanoke.
   He said he was unaware of any radio communication between the
pilot and ground controllers.
</TEXT>
