<FIRST>u a AM-TankerAground 3rdLd-Writethru a0749 03-03 0883</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Aground, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0749,0901</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike Team To Clean Up Oil Spill From Grounded Tanker</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 2nd to UPDATE with plan to free tanker,
picks up 3rd graf, pvs: `Oil washed ...; SUBS 8th graf, `A local . ..,
to CORRECT first reference to Les, sted Lee, Rogers; SUBS 21st graf, ``We
do ..., to DELETE redundant first reference to Rogers.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos HU1, HU2; LaserGraphic NY45</HEAD>
<UNK>By STEVE ELLIOTT ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fleet of tugboats and salvage ships worked in
rough seas and gusty wind Friday to refloat a grounded tanker and
stop any more of its cargo of 3.7 million gallons of crude oil from
reaching Oahu's beaches.
   Some of the 117,000 gallons of fuel and crude that spilled from
the 800-foot tanker continued to leak and washed ashore along a one-
to two-mile stretch of shore at Barbers Point on Oahu's southwest
coast, according to Coast Guard Lt. Brad Nelson.
   Capt. Gordon Piche, commanding officer of the Marine Safety
Office, said tugboat crews planned to try to free the ship at high
tide at 2 a.m. Saturday.
   Crews were unloading ballast water Friday afternoon and preparing
to remove some of the crude oil onto a barge, he said.
   Oil washed up on a beach where a popular tourist luau is held,
prompting the state Department of Health to post ``Polluted Waters''
signs, and at other areas as far as two miles to the north, said
Coast Guard spokesman Dennis Hubbard.
   Helicopter crews determined the oil slick was not edging toward
Honolulu, said Coast Guard spokesman David Santos.
   ``It's staying close to Barbers Point, and not drifting that
much,'' Santos said.
   Tugboat crews reported Friday morning that no more oil was
escaping from the Exxon Houston, according to Leonard Alcantara,
Honolulu attorney for Exxon Co. USA. The ship's 23 crewmembers were
not injured and remained aboard, he said.
   The Coast Guard's Pacific Area Strike Team was on its way from
the West Coast with equipment to clean up the spill, Nelson said.
   A local oil spill cleanup cooperative, called the Clean Islands
Council, was activated and on the scene, said Les Rogers, spokesman
for Exxon Co. USA, the Houston-based domestic oil and gas division
of Exxon Corp.
   ``In addition, Exxon has initiated response steps, including
authorization of more tugs, if needed, to free the vessel,'' he said.
   Elsewhere, an oil slick was spotted Friday off sensitive marine
reserves in the northern Florida Keys, but Coast Guard officials
said the spill did not appear to be a threat to the area.
   Parks in the area reported small gobs of tar washing up, and said
there did not appear to be major damage. Coast Guard spokesman Joe
Dye said dead birds were found out near the oil, but it was not
clear if they were killed by the slick.
   ``We have no idea where it came from,'' he said. ``There are
apparently no ships in the area.''
   In Antarctica, the second oil spill in a month has been brought
under control by Chilean navy personnel using chemical solvents to
fight a kilometer-long slick created by a grounded Peruvian
scientific ship, a Chilean navy spokesman said Friday. Leaks in two
damaged tanks on the Humboldt were sealed by divers, he said.
   On Jan. 28, an Argentine navy ship, the Bahia Paraiso, ran
aground off an Antarctic peninsula some 300 miles from the site of
the Humboldt's accident, creating a major oil slick. It was
eventually cleaned up by ships and personnel from Argentina, Chile
and the United States.
   The Hawaii spill occurred Thursday evening about 15 miles from
Honolulu, but an Oahu Civil Defense spokesman said it was unlikely
the oil would reach famed Waikiki Beach to the east.
   ``The chances of that happening are very, very slim,'' said
spokesman Frank Apel. ``It's just too far away.''
   There was no trace of oil along the shoreline beyond Barbers
Point, Nelson said, and there was no immediate move to close any
beaches. There also was no evidence of affected marine life or
seabirds being washed ashore, he said.
   Currents normally would carry the oil to the northwest away from
Honolulu, but gusty wind was blowing it in the opposite direction,
he said.
   Nine tugboats worked to refloat the Exxon Houston, which broke
free of its moorings and apparently drifted onto a reef during rough
seas Thursday evening, Nelson said.
   The ship's hull suffered minor damage, but was sitting in 16 feet
of water and was in no danger of sinking, Nelson said.
   ``We do know that one of the ship's fuel tanks and at least one
of the empty cargo tanks have been breached,'' said Rogers.
   The vessel was three-tenths of mile off Barbers Point on Oahu's
southwest coast and had just unloaded 16.8 million gallons of Alaska
North Slope crude oil to the Hawaiian Independent Refinery when it
broke free of its moorings, Nelson said.
   The crew initially declined Coast Guard assistance, but the
ship's captain, Kevin Dick, later reported that the vessel was
``hard aground'' Nelson said.
   An estimated 25,000 gallons of crude oil spilled when the tanker
broke free during unloading, and 92,000 gallons of heavy bunker fuel
oil spilled when an aft tank was ruptured when the tanker went
aground, Nelson said.
</TEXT>
