<FIRST>r i AM-ChildGiveaway     03-03 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Giveaway,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rejected Refugees Seek Home For Their Children Through Ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chilean couple who were denied political
asylum in Norway tried to give away their five children Thursday by
advertising for a foster home in a Norwegian newspaper.
   ``Isn't there a nice Norwegian family that wants to be parents to
Oscar, 10, Luis, 6, Nicolas, 4, Natalia, 2, and Patricia, three
months?'' asked the couple in the Faedrelandsvennen newspaper in the
southern town of Kristiansand.
   Juan Patricio Arrancibia Collao and his wife Raquel Quesada
Molina took the painful step because they feared their children
would be killed or disappear if they returned to Chile, the national
news agency NTB reported.
   ``This is the first time we've seen anything like this,'' said
Tove Johnsen, manager of the Kristiansand Immigrants' Office.
   ``I consider it very serious that a family has reacted so
strongly to a rejection that they would give their children up for
adoption rather than take them out of the country,'' she told the
news service.
   The couple's attorney, Sverre Nordmo, told NTB they still can
appeal their deportation order by April 6, and that he was surprised
when they took such desperate action.
   When he arrived here in March 1988, Collao told officials he had
been tortured in a Chilean prison in late 1987. His family followed
him to Norway the following month, NTB said.
   Most of the 900 or so Chileans who arrived during the first half
of 1988 risk being deported because Norwegian authorities believe
they would be in no real danger in their homeland, according to the
Norwegian Ministry of Justice.
   By the latest count from the state Bureau of Statistics there
were 3,747 Chileans living in Norway in July 1988.
</TEXT>
