<FIRST>r a AM-BrooklynDrugs     03-03 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brooklyn Drugs,0329</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Six Charged in `Business of Death' ^By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six leaders of a violent, multimillion-dollar
crack ring were charged Thursday with nine murders and seven
attempted murders, officials said.
   The defendants, all from Brooklyn, were in ``the business of
death,'' said District Attorney Elizabeth Holtzman. ``These gang
members allegedly killed not only members of rival drug gangs but
tried to enforce their writ by killing their own employees to
enforce discipline.''
   The leaders also were accused of murdering three innocent
bystanders in the course of operating the multimillion-dollar crack
ring, Holtzman said.
   ``I think we got one of the major gangs,'' said New York Police
Chief of Detectives, Robert Colangelo. ``There are several others
but none have its scope and violence.''
   A 70-count indictment charged the six men with enterprise
corruption under the state's version of the federal racketeering
statute. They also face numerous counts of murder, attempted murder,
assault, weapons and drug charges.
   The crimes outlined in the indictment occurred between June 1987
and last month. If convicted, the defendants would face up to life
in prison.
   The drug ring had about 50 members and six retail locations in
east New York that each brought in $10,000 to $25,000 daily,
officials said.
   ``The group was particularly callous in terms of sellin to
youths,'' said Colangelo, who noted that two of the locations were
near public schools.
   The gang's alleged leader was identified as Samuel Edmonson, 28,
who was on parole for a robbery conviction.
   The other defendants are John Amante, 31; Kyle Patterson, 24;
Victor Breland, 32; Winston Easterling, 19; and Robinson, 28.
Edmonson and Amante were arrested Wednesday and the other four were
arrested earlier, officials said.
   In addition to the arrests, authorities seized $106,000 in cash,
various guns, more than 400 vials of crack, the highly addictive
cocaine derivative, and three ounces of cocaine, Holtzman said.
</TEXT>
