<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0001EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Communists     03-03 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Communists,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Town Mayor Slain, Rebel Leader Rejects Conditions For Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communist rebel leader on Thursday
rejected President Corazon Aquino's demand that the guerrillas lay
down their arms in exchange for peace talks, and guerrillas killed
an outspoken anti-communist mayor.
   Luis Jalandoni, foreign liaison officer of the National
Democratic Front based in the Netherlands, said in an interview with
a Manila radio station that the rebels were willing to find a
peaceful solution to the 20-year conflict.
   ``The (Front) is very willing to find a solution, a negotiated
political settlement for a just and lasting peace,'' said Jalandoni,
a former priest. ``But the condition that we should surrender is a
pre-condition that is impossible.''
   Last week, Mrs. Aquino said she was willing to renew peace talks
if the 24,000-strong New People's Army lays down its arms.
   The Front is an umbrella organization of 12 Marxist groups,
including the Communist Party of the Philippines and its armed wing,
the New Peoples Army.
   Jalandoni said Mrs. Aquino's stand showed the president ``closed
her mind to the reality that the NDF is a political force that has
been struggling for years, that it has influence over 10,000
villages and that it cannot surrender areas and people who
sacrificed because of their principles and programs.''
   The military claims Jalandoni, who has both Dutch and Filipino
citizenship, is a member of the central committee of the outlawed
Communist Party. Jalandoni is believed to be in charge of rebel
fund-raising activities in Europe.
   Mrs. Aquino opened peace talks with the Front in 1986 but
negotiations collapsed in January 1987 after she refused rebel
power-sharing demands.
   Last week, Front spokesman Satur Ocampo said the rebels would
consider resuming peace talks if the Aquino government agreed to
close the six American military bases here when their lease expires
in 1991.
   Also Thursday, police said Capistrano Legaspi, mayor of the town
of Kinogitan in Misamis Oriental province, was slain Wednesday by
three suspected rebel assassins.
   The report said Legaspi was waiting for a ride home when the
rebels approached and opened fire in the town about 470 miles
southeast of Manila.
   Legaspi was an outspoken opponent of the rebel movement.
</TEXT>
