<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--CausesOfDeath 1stLd-Writethru a0690salarywentto$1.085millionanusesOfDeathContinueDownwardTrend
03-03 0556</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Causes Of Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0690,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Of Big Three U.S. Causes Of Death Continue Downward Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 11th graf, ``There are ..., to UPDATE
with comment on declining cancer rate.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mortality rates in the United States for two of
the three leading causes of death _ heart disease and stroke _ are
headed down, the national Centers for Disease Control said Thursday.
   However, the second-leading cause of death, cancer, is going up.
   The CDC said the U.S. death rate from heart disease in 1987 was
313 per 100,000 people, down from 318 the year before. For stroke _
or cerebrovascular disease _ the rate was 61 per 100,000, down from
62.
   There were 196 cancer deaths in 1987 for every 100,000 Americans,
up from 195 the year before.
   Heart disease, cancer and stroke account for about two-thirds of
the 2 million deaths that occur in this country every year, the
Atlanta-based CDC said in its weekly report.
   In actual numbers, heart disease killed 762,820 of the 2.2
million Americans who died in 1987. Cancer killed 477,190, and
stroke killed 149,220. A year earlier, 2.1 million Americans died,
including 765,490 from heart disease, 469,376 from cancer and
149,643 from stroke, according to Dr. Harry Rosenberg, a researcher
with the National Center for Health Statistics.
   ``What we are seeing ... is the continuation of some long-term
trends,'' Rosenberg said.
   The decline in deaths from heart disease and stroke has been
going on for a decade, said Thomas Thom, an epidemiologist with the
National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute. Most experts believe the
decline can be attributed to improvements in personal health,
greater prevention of disease, improvement in medical care for heart
or stroke patients, or all of those factors, Thom said.
   ``The decline is ... very real, and very consistent,'' he said.
``There's got to be something doing it.''
   Specifically, he cited trends toward quitting smoking,
controlling high blood pressure and lowering cholesterol levels, as
well as ``increased physical activity and, generally, health
consciousness.'' At the same time, cardiac intensive care units have
come into widespread use in hospitals, and heart surgery has become
commonplace.
   ``There are plenty of reasons to think all those reasons
contributed,'' he said.
   Rosenberg said the cancer rate, which has been rising as those
Americans age whose lifestyles included more smoking and more
unhealthy foods, should fall in the coming years because of changing
lifestyles among the young.
   ``We see the beginnings of the overall decrease in cancer
mortality in a decrease among all age groups of people younger than
55, particularly young males,'' he said.
   Among 45- to 54-year-olds, Rosenberg said the cancer rate dropped
from 181 per 100,000 in 1979 to 166 per 100,000 in 1986. He said
preventive measures of the past two decades, such as improved diet
and less smoking, contributed to that drop.
   Complete mortality figures from 1988 are not yet available,
Rosenberg said.
   The mortality rate from heart disease was showing a slight
increase from 1987 levels in the 12 months from October 1987 to
September 1988, he said, but that might be traced, in part, to an
influenza epidemic last winter which preyed upon those at increased
risk of problems from flu _ such as patients with chronic heart
disease.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
