<FIRST>r i AM-HelicopterCrash     03-03 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spanish Helicopter Explodes, Killing Three Crew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish air force helicopter burst into
flames over Madrid on Thursday and crashed into a heavily populated
area, killing the three crew members but causing no injuries on the
ground, police said.
   The front of the helicopter hurtled into the empty recess area of
the Blas de Otero secondary school, said a Madrid police official
who asked not to be identified.
   He said the tail landed 60 yards away in a private courtyard.
   ``The students were apparently inside the building, in class, at
the time of the accident,'' he said.
   The police official said firefighters quickly extinguished the
burning wreckage in the heavily populated southeast Aluche
neighborhood and added the crash had no impact on a shopping center
about 100 yards away.
   ``There was an explosion, then (the helicopter) started doing
somersaults and the rotor broke loose and then the tail
disintegrated,'' a witness to the accident told Spanish National
Radio.
   ``It's a good thing the helicopter pilot managed to avoid
crashing into the tall buildings that surround the area,'' Madrid
Mayor Juan Barranco told reporters on the scene.
   ``Thanks to the cool courage of the pilot there weren't any more
deaths,'' the mayor said.
   Air Force spokesman Cmdr. Julian Fernandez Torregrosa said the
accident killed the helicoper's pilot, co-pilot and mechanic, whom
he identified as Capt. Alfredo Vidal Montero, 33; Capt. Ramon
Garrido de la Parra, 30; and 2nd Lt. Jose Rodriguez Montero.
   Fernandez said the French-built Puma helicopter was on a routine
training mission.
</TEXT>
