<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0118EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Trade     03-03 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Trade,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan, France To Cut Iranian Oil Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan and France plan to cut imports of Iranian oil,
officials said Thursday, but neither depicted the move as being in
reaction to a death threat against novelist Salman Rushdie by Iran's
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   A French oil company official, however, said the French decision
was linked to worsening relations with Iran after Khomeini, Iran's
revolutionary and religious patriarch, attacked Rushdie over his
book ``The Satanic Verses.''
   Many Moslems find the book blasphemous.
   Japan's cutback will be up to 20 percent over the next three
months. Officials in the trade and foreign ministryies said it was
because of a seasonal decline in demand and not motivated by the
Rushdie affair.
   ``It's true that there will be a decline in coming months but it
has nothing to do with political issues,'' said Tsukasa Kawada,
deputy director of the Foreign Ministry's Energy Resources Division.
   In Paris, an Industry Ministry spokesman said oil companies were
urged to slacken imports about 10 days ago.
   While France issued no formal directive on cutting oil imports, a
senior official from the Industry Ministry's hydrocarbons service
``suggested'' to French oil companies that they trim imports
following Khomeini's death threats against Rushdie, according to
industry sources speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The suggestion was not overtly linked to the Rushdie matter.
Officials suggested only that a high level of imports was
``inappropriate'' at this time.
   But one official at a major French oil company said, ``It was
suggested to us it would be inappropriate for us to increase our
imports of Iranian crude, or to maintain them at a high level, in
the present diplomatic context.''
   Khomeini's call on Feb. 14 for Moslems to kill Rushdie provoked
some economic backlash in Europe, notably West Germany. All member
nations of the European Economic Community recalled their
ambassadors from Tehran.
   Japan condemned the death edict but did not withdraw its
ambassador.
   So far this year, Japanese purchases of Iranian crude averaged
about 300,000 barrels a day, greater than in previous months because
of the larger winter demand. Purchases are likely to drop to
240,000-250,000 barrels in the second quarter, oil company officials
say.
   Last year, Iranian oil accounted for 5.7 percent of total
Japanese oil imports, a drop of 18.3 percent from 1987.
</TEXT>
