<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A city program considered a national model for
steering contracts to minority businesses was overturned as too
``intrusive'' by the state Supreme Court, a ruling officials say
could halt contracting for months.
   The court based Thursday's 7-0 decision on a U.S. Supreme Court
ruling in January that overturned a similar program in Richmond, Va.
It was the high court's first reversal of an affirmative action
program after years of upholding them.
   The state court said Atlanta failed to produce enough evidence of
past discrimination to justify its program. It also said the program
was too broadly drawn and that the city had not considered ``less
intrusive'' methods of increasing minority participation in city
contracts. It was not immediately clear whether the ruling on behalf
of the American Subcontractors Association effectively dismantles
the program.
