<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Profile     03-03 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Profile,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Airlines At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is a look at Eastern Airlines, which is facing a strike by
its Machinists at 12:01 a.m. EST Saturday unless negotiators reach
an unexpected breakthrough in a 17-month-old contract dispute.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Owner: The 60-year-old airline has been owned by Texas Air Corp.,
headed by Chairman Frank Lorenzo, since 1986.
   Headquarters: Miami.
   Employees: 31,200, including 8,500 members of the Machinists
union, which includes mechanics, bag handlers and other ground
workers; 3,500 pilots and 5,900 flight attendants.
   Size of fleet: 250 jets.
   Cities served: 118, with its major markets in South Florida, the
Caribbean, the East Coast and Latin America.
   Number of flights: 1,040 daily.
   Passengers: 100,000 average daily.
   Main strike issues: Eastern, which claims it lost $1 billion in
the past decade and is losing more than $1 million a day, is seeking
$150 million in wage concessions. The Machinists are seeking $50
million in raises.
   Where negotiations stand: The National Mediation Board in
Washington is trying to get both sides to reach a settlement before
the strike deadline. The board has asked President Bush to appoint
an emergency panel that could delay the strike 60 days. The White
House said Thursday that no decision had been made.
   In the event of a strike: Eastern has vowed to continue flying,
although company officials refuse to divulge contingency plans. The
company promised passengers would be rerouted or given refunds on
any canceled flights. The Machinists have threatened to picket other
airlines, ships and railroads, and AFL-CIO officials have said they
want their 14 million members to support the Eastern Machinists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
