<DOCNO> AP890303-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0344EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Showdown Bjt   03-03 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Showdown, Bjt,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo, Bryan Head Opposite Sides</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Eastern Airlines showdown pits one of the
airline industry's most feared bosses against a union leader who may
be the industry's most stubborn.
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, 48, is a Queens, N.Y.,
son of Spanish immigrants, Harvard Business School graduate and
aggressive builder of the nation's largest airline company.
   He's had no success dealing with Machinists union District 100
President Charles E. Bryan, 55, a West Virginia-born mechanic and
magnetic, self-educated man who says he takes his strategies from
Zen, the Bible, Gandhi, Martin Luther King Jr. and the ancient
Chinese author Sun-tzu's ``The Art of War.''
   With a Machinists union strike deadline set for midnight EST
Friday, about the only point the two driven men agree on is that
Eastern may not survive a strike.
   Lorenzo bought Eastern three years ago with a warning that
``there ain't no Santa Claus,'' and his new management sent
Eastern's usually tense labor relations plummeting to new lows with
wage concession demands, toughened work rules and thousands of
layoffs, firings and suspensions.
   His Eastern management has added to a union-busting reputation he
gained when he ended a labor confrontation at Continental Airlines
in 1983 by taking the carrier into bankruptcy reorganization and
getting union contracts abrogated.
   Texas Air has outraged Eastern unions by taking over Eastern's
computerized reservations system, collecting tens of millions of
dollars in ``management fees'' and loans from Eastern, and agreeing
to sell Eastern's profitable and prestigious Northeast shuttle
service to developer Donald Trump. That $365 million sale is not
final.
   Management says it has tried to work with Bryan, but that the
union leader wants to run the airline himself. A booklet titled
``Charlie Says ...'' put out recently by Eastern warns: ``If Charlie
isn't stopped, he will destroy Eastern.''
   Former Eastern chairman Frank Borman says Bryan has ``a
certifiably insane dream'' of running the airline himself, and
Borman recently compared Bryan to cult leader Jim Jones, who led a
mass suicide of followers in Guyana in 1978.
   Bryan, elected president of Eastern's largest union in 1980 and
overwhelmingly re-elected twice, got Borman to back down and give
pay increases in 1983 on the last day of a Machinists strike
deadline.
   In 1986, with Eastern facing bankruptcy, Bryan refused to join
the pilots and flight attendants in making wage concessions unless
they were tied to Borman's ouster. Eastern's board of directors
refused, and sold the company to Lorenzo, who built tiny,
money-losing Texas International into the Houston-based Texas Air
Corp. that took over Continental Airlines, New York Air, People
Express, Frontier and other small carriers.
   Lorenzo, who initially indicated he wouldn't involve himself in
Eastern's labor situation, ignored a post-sale telegram from Bryan
asking for a meeting. But last year, as negotiations with the
Machinists stalemated and Eastern unions fought management with
myriad lawsuits and political lobbying, Lorenzo had dinner with
Bryan in Houston.
   The dinner only led to more disputes and Bryan continued to hope
for a buyout of Eastern. Bryan contends that Eastern has been badly
mismanaged for years at the employees' expense, and that workers
would increase productivity and service with more input into how the
company is run.
   Corporate kingpins Carl Icahn, T. Boone Pickens and Trump have
all been approached by Eastern unions about buying Eastern, but
Texas Air, which has posted record losses since taking over the
airline, has said there are no buyers on the horizon.
   Bryan, a mechanic since 1956 at an airline whose last strike was
in 1966, has seen his union rolls reduced from 12,000 to 8,500 since
the Texas Air takeover.
   ``Our people have been frustrated, there have been attempts to
provoke wildcat strikes,'' Bryan said recently. ``They have been
brutalized by management that doesn't care about the company's
future.''
   While promising ``a wing-ding of a strike,'' Bryan also worried
that the company may not survive.
   ``We've fought them as long as we could and we've had some
success,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, our system doesn't seem to look
out for the working man.''
   Lorenzo, meanwhile, made a last-ditch personal appeal to Eastern
pilots this week. In a videotape showing a shirt-sleeved Lorenzo in
a homey easy chair, he urged: ``Eastern is either going to make it
through this period, make the changes that are necessary and go on
and succeed ... or I'm afraid Eastern is going to go through this
juncture and perhaps end up in the corporate graveyard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
