<DOCNO> AP890303-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Europe-AirlineReservations     03-03 0508</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Airline Reservations,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europe To Urge U.S. To Amend Computer Reservations System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western European aviation officials have
urged Washington to end a built-in bias against European air
carriers in the five computerized reservation systems used by U.S.
airlines and travel agents.
   These systems are programmed to favor U.S. carriers though
European airlines fly the same routes to Europe and in much less
time, the European officials said Thursday.
   ``Consumers suffer from not always being given ready access to
the best (flight) information,'' by U.S. computerized reservation
systems, Edward Hudson, secretary of the 22-nation European Civil
Aviation Conference, told reporters.
   Representatives of the two biggest U.S. computerized reservation
services, Apollo and Sabre, said the criticism came at a time when
they were taking steps to correct the situation.
   ``I'm surprised that they would be saying this now with all the
things that have happened in the recent past,'' said Karen Cook, a
spokeswoman for American Airlines' Sabre system.
   Since December, Sabre has offered travel agents two ways of
displaying flight information, one of which is more favorable to
European airlines, Ms. Cook said. Apollo plans to offer two display
options starting later this month, according to John McIntyre,
director of products marketing for Covia, the parent of Apollo.
   The European accusations echo accusations by U.S. airlines that
American and United Air Lines discriminated against other carriers
with their reservation systems. Since 1984 the Civil Aeronautics
Board has required the systems not to give any preferential
treatment.
   Hudson said he would raise the issue in a meeting with U.S.
Department of Transportation officials this month. To date, ``There
has been a marked reluctance from the U.S. government to open its
ears to what has been said by the Europeans,'' he added.
   Reservations made through U.S. computerized reservation systems
often involve ``unnecessarily lengthy journey times with long
overlays at connecting points'' because the computers favor U.S.
carriers, Hudson said.
   He said they list U.S. carriers on the first screen while flights
of European carriers are tucked away on remote screens that booking
agents do not check unless travellers say at what hour they want to
leave.
   The five U.S. systems are known as Apollo, Sabre, Pars, Datas-II
and System One. Hudson said none gives priority to flights to Europe
where warranted.
   As an example, he cited a non-stop San Francisco-to-Paris flight
on France's UTA airline that he said is up to 5{ hours faster than
flights on major U.S. carriers that make stopovers. Yet Sabre puts
the UTA flight on screen 9 rather than on the first screen, he said.
   Flights of Air France, British Airways, Lufthansa, Alitalia and
SAS get similar treatment though they get travelers from California
to Europe hours faster than U.S. carriers, he said.
   Hudson said the 22 ECAC nations will issue next week rules of
conduct for Western Europe's two main computerized reservation
systems, Amadeus and Galileo. These rules, he said, give
non-European carriers first-screen priority if their flights are
more convenient. He called on the U.S. government to do likewise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
