<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0347EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TVAds-Rakolta Bjt   03-03 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Ads-Rakolta, Bjt,0656</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Woman Gets Ads Pulled From TV Program</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Material in grafs 11-13 may be objectionable to some readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Rakolta won a skirmish and now she wants to
start a battle against what she says are sexually oriented and
violent programs that cut into the network television fare her
children can watch.
   ``The American family is beng painted into a corner. It's an
invasion of my privacy at this point,'' Rakolta said Thursday.
   A flurry of letters starting in January brought Rakolta apologies
from advertisers on the top-rated, prime-time ``Married ... With
Children'' program. Some pulled their ads on the Fox Broadcasting
Co. series.
   Rakolta said Thursday she objects to having to monitor prime-time
television for shows she doesn't want her younger children to watch.
``If people want that stuff, they can pay for it, or rent it, or go
to the movies,'' she said.
   Rakolta said she intends to start a group, or join existing ones,
to organize national boycotts of advertisers.
   ``One person can really make a difference if they push the right
buttons. And the right buttons are not the producers in Hollywood,
they're the people that pay the money for the show,'' she said.
   The activism is new, said Rakolta, 40, who lives in affluent
Bloomfield Hills in suburban Detroit. She has daughters ages 18, 10
and 9, and a son, 8. Her husband, John Rakolta, is president of a
large construction company.
   ``I've never been involved in a cause. I've been involved in
civic groups, but nothing cause-oriented,'' she said.
   But she said that when she and her children watched ``Married ...
With Children'' one Sunday night in January, she ended up shooing
the children out of the room.
   The situation comedy, which began in 1987 and is Fox's most
successful show, is about a blue-collar family headed by shoe-store
clerk Al Bundy. Rakolta said the first show she saw featured a man's
visit to a lingerie store.
   ``In the store, one woman removed her bra for strangers, asking
how she looked. It showed a man that worked there, an older man,
walking around in a garter belt. They mentioned vibrators on the
show,'' Rakolta said.
   ``I was thinking it was a family program because it was prime
time, 8:30 p.m. I was horrified. I wanted to know what kind of
sponsors would sponsor a show like this,'' she said.
   Rakolta said she watched other episodes to see who advertised. On
one, she said, the father asked his children, with his wife standing
nearby, what women and ``dog do do'' have in common, and told them,
``They get easier to pick up as they get older.''
   Since Rakolta wrote them, Procter &amp; Gamble Co., McDonald's Corp.,
Kimberly-Clark Corp. and Tambrands Inc. have told their advertising
agencies not to buy time on the program. The president of Coca-Cola
USA, Ira Herbert, said his company will screen future episodes more
closely.
   ``I must tell you that I am corporately, professionally, and
personally embarrassed that one of our commercials appeared in this
particularly unsuitable program episode,'' Herbert wrote Rakolta.
   Fox officials defended the show. The Bundy family is ``a comedic
counterpoint to other fictional television families who enjoy above
average incomes, greater opportunities and have more refined
tastes,'' wrote Don R. Bay, a Fox vice president.
   Some episodes in the parody of life ``in a lower socioeconomic
family'' may offend some viewers, wrote Gary Lieberthal, chairman of
its producer, Columbia Pictures Television _ whose parent company is
owned by Coca-Cola Co. ``Hopefully, many people (though we know not
all) will be entertained by the outrageously absurd lives and
off-center values of the Bundy family.''
   Rakolta said she didn't see the humor. ``They're exploiting
women. They're stereotyping poor people,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
