<DOCNO> AP890303-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SchoolAds     03-03 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-School Ads,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whittle Reports No Advertiser Defections From TV News Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The architect of a plan to send commercials along
with a news show into classrooms says advertisers backing a test run
of the program are standing firm despite growing criticism of the
proposal.
   Christopher Whittle, head of Whittle Communications LP of
Knoxville, Tenn., said eight sponsors have signed contracts to buy
80 percent of the commercial time available during the test that
starts Monday.
   ``No one who has signed has even called and said they were
worried,'' he said Thursday in response to reports that a second
major education group has gone on record opposing commercials in
school.
   Whittle refused to identify the eight sponsors, saying it would
become evident who they are once the test run starts in six schools
on March 6.
   As part of the test, Whittle has equipped six schools with about
$50,000 each in television monitors, recording equipment and
sattellite dishes so they can receive the 12-minute daily news show
he is producing for teen-agers.
   The schools, in exchange, are to run the show each school day.
   The show, called Channel One, will include two minutes of paid
commercials. The advertising has outraged some educators, who say
big business should not be allowed that kind of access to the
classroom.
   The National Parent-Teacher Association said Wednesday that its
22-member executive committee opposed sending commercials into the
schools. Earlier this week, the National Association of Secondary
School Principals voted to urge principals to avoid programs that
have commercials.
   Levi Strauss &amp; Co., the San Francisco-based apparel maker, is one
of the sponsors of the test, but Levi's marketing manager, Dan Chew,
said the uproar hasn't prompted the company to reconsider its
support.
   ``We are very sensitive to the public debate and we are
monitoring it and listening as closely as anyone else,'' he said.
   But he said that public reaction to the idea of including ads on
a news show for schools is only one issue on ``a long list of
criteria'' for making a decision on whether to continue advertising
on the show if Whittle proceeds with plans to make it available next
year in 8,000 schools.
   Whittle said many schools would not be able to afford a topical,
daily news program like he is producing or the hardware. He says
allowing two minutes of commercials is a reasonable way to finance
it.
   He said his company has made presentations to 15 advertisers
seeking their support for the program and that only three, whom he
declined to identify, have declined.
   In addition to the eight that signed contracts, he said he is
continuing negotations with four others and is hopeful that two of
three of them will buy the remaining commercial inventory.
   Lou Nagy, spokesman for sneaker maker Converse Inc. in North
Reading, Mass., said Converse isn't interested in being a sponsor,
though it counts on the teen-age consumers that Whittle is courting.
   ``Our feeling is that there are plenty of opportunities to reach
the teen-age audience and we just feel that doing it in the
classroom is maybe overdoing it a little bit,'' he said.
   In another development Thursday, Whittle said it had reached an
agreement to send non-sponsored programming to the test schools from
the Pacific Mountain Network, which represents public television
stations in 13 western states.
   An unspecified number of programs will be delivered over the same
satellite system that carries the Channel One program, and schools
are free to use the shows as they choose.
   Whittle already publishes a number of magazines and sponsored
posters that are distributed in schools across the country, and he
notes that the advertising in those publications has not come under
fire.
   But critics say a sponsored television show that is being shown
in classrooms will be more difficult than other media for students
to ignore.
</TEXT>
