<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0443EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AdBacklash Bjt   03-03 0775</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ad Backlash, Bjt,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>Racy TV Show Loses Several Major Advertisers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defection of several advertisers from the
television comedy ``Married... With Children'' highlights concern
among image-conscious corporations over TV's increasingly racy fare,
some industry insiders said.
   Two major advertisers quit buying time on the Fox Broadcasting
Co. situation comedy. Others have spurned selected episodes for fear
the show's frank language and references to sex would offend
viewers, executives of the advertisers said Thursday.
   Advertising already is tough to find for ``tabloid TV'' programs
such as ``Geraldo'' that delve into kinky sex, devil worship and
similarly salacious subjects, advertising executives say.
   Some defectors from ``Married,'' which is the fledgling Fox's
top-rated show, were influenced by an energetic letter-writing
campaign by a Detroit-area mother, Terry Rakolta, spokesmen said.
   The show, about a blue-collar family named Bundy, features
references to sex and bathroom humor, buxom women and frequent
portrayals of the husband berating his wife.
   Two advertisers, Procter &amp; Gamble Co. and American Home Products
Corp., bought some ads on the show but have decided against further
sponsorship, spokesmen said Thursday. Johnson &amp; Johnson and
McDonald's Corp. officials said they had decided against running
national advertising on the show, though individual, locally
purchased ads for the two had run.
   Coca-Cola USA, whose president, Ira Herbert, wrote an apology to
Mrs. Rakolta, continues to screen ``Married'' episodes for content,
but hasn't found one suitable for advertising since her complaint
Jan. 15, said spokesman Tony Tortorici.
   Advertisers' concerns were summed up by Procter &amp; Gamble
spokeswoman Kelly Gillespie: ``We felt that the whole theme of the
show is basically one we do not want to be associated with. We were
concerned about the negative portrayal of American family life.''
   Fox, which purposefully appeals to the young adult audiences
advertisers covet in its efforts to build a fourth television
network, hasn't had any trouble selling ads on the show, which is
broadcast Sunday evenings, said spokesman Brad Turell.
   ``The show is completely sold out,'' he said, adding that news
reports of Mrs. Rakolta's campaign prompted calls of support from
viewers.
   ``We have received literally hundreds of telephone calls today
from across the country from viewers saying that this one woman's
opinion is getting too much attention and hoping that we won't
change the show,'' Turell said.
   Procter &amp; Gamble, which makes hundreds of household products,
bought ads on several ``Married'' episodes last year, stopped from
October through December then sponsored two shows in January, Ms.
Gillespie said. After receiving Mrs. Rakolta's letter, officials
reviewed the show and decided against further ads, she said.
   American Home Products, which makes goods ranging from Jiffy Pop
to Woolite, had already decided to disassociate itself from the show
before receiving Mrs. Rakolta's letter, said spokeswoman Carol
Emerling in New York.
   Tambrands, which produces feminine hygiene products such as
Tampax, planned to advertise on two ``Married'' episodes but
canceled the second after a review prompted by Mrs. Rakolta's
letters, said Paul Konney, a spokesman in the company's New York
headquarters.
   Advertisers face a dilemma in deciding whether to sponsor racy
shows, which often attract big audiences but may offend some vocal
consumers.
   So-called tabloid TV shows like ``Geraldo'' have difficulty
attracting advertisers because of what many see as their
exploitation of the weaker side of humanity.
   A recent survey of advertisers and ad buyers found resistance to
such shows, topped by the often-outrageous ``The Morton Downey Jr.''
talk show, said Dean McCarthy, vice president of Harrington, Righter
&amp; Parsons, a New York firm that helps television stations sell air
time.
   Virtually all big companies have guidelines for what kind of
shows are acceptable for their ads, and most hire screening
companies to check shows in advance for problems.
   As television presses the outer limits of taste _ boosted by more
lenient federal regulations and greater competition for ads with
other media _ finding an appropriate spot for an ad be difficult,
said McDonald's spokeswoman Stephanie Skurdy.
   ``Ours is a children's and family business,'' Ms. Skurdy said
from the company's Oak Brook, Ill., headquarters. ``It has become
increasingly difficult to find family programming on prime-time
television.''
   But Paul Isaacson, vice president of Young &amp; Rubicam, a New York
advertising agency, said complaints about shows' content didn't
appear any more frequent now than they ever have.
   Those who seek to influence television content through pressure
on advertisers are attempting censorship, said Carol Sobel, an
American Civil Liberties Union attorney.
   ``If you don't want to watch it then don't watch it,'' Ms. Sobel
said. ``I think what is inappropriate is to force your views on
anyone else.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0450EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-RetailSales     03-03 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retail Sales,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Rates To Restrain Spending But Retailers Unlikely To Suffer
Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economists say rising interest rates have started
to influence people's spending decisions, but purchases of clothing
and other everday items will be among the last things affected.
   There was no evidence of a slowdown in consumer spending in
reports Thursday from the nation's largest retailers, which showed
many of them enjoyed healthy sales gains in February.
   A continuing turnaround in women's apparel and renewed demand for
other consumer and household goods contributed to last month's gains
for department stores, discount chains and general merchandise
vendors.
   Retail sales measure important aspects of consumer spending
activity, which accounts for about two-thirds of all U.S. economic
activity.
   Lawrence Kudlow, chief economist at the investment banking firm
Bear, Stearns &amp; Co., said the recent rise in interest rates, partly
reflecting the Federal Reserve Board's effort to squeeze
inflationary pressures, may be changing people's minds about
spending.
   ``I think we are already in the early stages of a slowdown in
consumer spending,'' Kudlow said. ``You are seeing a higher savings
rate, which is the flip side of slower spending.''
   Higher interest rates will have the most impact on purchases
typically financed over time, such as cars and home appliances.
Jeffrey Feiner, a retail industry analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.,
said the effect on sales of clothing and routine items will be much
more limited.
   ``We still remain relatively sanguine about the retailing
outlook, given the improvement in women's apparel as well as our
belief that retailers will maintain very strong control over
inventories and expenses,'' he said.
   For many of the retailers, February marked the start of their
1989 financial year. Balance sheets showed signs of improvement last
year, analysts said, due largely to unexpectedly brisk business
before and after Christmas.
   February typically is a low-volume month as merchants prepare for
a seasonal shopping pickup in the spring. But analysts detected
favorable omens in the latest tallies.
   One good sign was stronger sales of apparel, apparently because
women are finding the latest styles more appealing than last year's
fashions.
   Limited Inc., the apparel retailer, said sales rose 22 percent in
the four weeks ended Feb. 25 from the year before and sales at
stores open at least a year _ called same-store sales _ went up by
19 percent.
   Retailers and industry analysts say same-store sales give a more
accurate reading of a company's performance than totals that include
sales at newly opened stores. Not every retailer reports same-store
sales.
   At Sears, Roebuck and Co., the nation's largest retailer, sales
of sporting goods, toys and auto accessories posted strong gains,
said Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of Sears
Merchandise Group.
   Sears, which on Wednesday inaugurated a new low-pricing policy at
all of its more than 800 stores, said sales for the four weeks ended
Feb. 25 went up 13.2 percent from the year-earlier level and
same-store sales rose 6.6 percent.
   K mart Chairman and Chief Executive Joseph E. Antonini said sales
of small appliances, home electronics and items in its pharmacy
division contributed to overall sales growth.
   K mart's sales for the four weeks ended Feb. 22 grew 8.3 percent
and sales at stores open a year or more were up by 3.5 percent.
   William R. Howell, chairman of J.C. Penney Co. Inc., said
promotions for Valentine's Day and President's Day boosted sales,
particularly for men's merchandise and home furnishings.
   Penney said sales in the four weeks ended Feb. 25 increased 5.3
percent and same-store sales gained 2.5 percent. The company has
discontinued lines such as home electronics, some sporting goods and
photographic equipment over the year and, excluding those lines,
sales for February rose 9.8 percent.
   Among other retailers reporting Thursday:
   Wal-Mart Stores Inc., the fast-growing discount and general
merchandise chain based in Bentonville, Ark., recorded a 25 percent
sales rise in February. Same-store sales rose 11 percent.
   Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp. said sales for the four
weeks ended Feb. 25 were up 11 percent over the year and same-store
sales rose 4.7 percent.
   The results reported Thursday were from most of the biggest
general merchandise chains and apparel retailers, excluding Campeau
Corp., R.H. Macy &amp; Co. and Batus Inc., which do not release monthly
figures. Unlike monthly retail sales figures released by the federal
government, they do not include sales at auto dealers, supermarkets
or restaurants.
</TEXT>
