<FIRST>r f PM-MinnetonkaCorp.     03-03 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Minnetonka Corp.,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minnetonka Corp. May Seek To Be Bought</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minnetonka Corp., maker of Calvin Klein
cosmetics, says it may offer itself for sale to maximize value for
its shareholders.
   ``Comparable high-margin, luxury product businesses are
commanding very high values in the private market,'' said Robert R.
Taylor, Minnetonka's chairman, chief executive officer and largest
individual shareholder.
   ``This underscores our belief that it is in the best interests of
our shareholders to explore the sale of the company,'' he said in a
statement Thursday.
   Taylor said Minnetonka, which designs, manufactures and markets
international lines of fragrance, personal care and leather
accessory products, has retained Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. Inc. as its
financial adviser to explore a possible sale and other alternatives
to benefit shareholders.
   Minnetonka on Wednesday reported a 1988 profit from continuing
operations of $15.8 million, up 56 percent from the $10.1 million of
1987. Earnings per share from continuing operations were 94 cents,
up 65 percent from 57 cents the previous year.
   Sales for the year rose 40 percent to $213.5 million, from $152.4
million in 1987.
   The company said its Calvin Klein cosmetics division accounted
for $157.7 million of total sales, up 52 percent from 1987, and had
a 66 percent increase in operating income to $27.7 million.
   ``The Calvin Klein cosmetics division has become the leading
contributor to Minnetonka's financial performance and has
consistently delivered exceptional growth and profitability,''
Taylor said.
   Minnetonka's 1988 results included the launching of its Calvin
Klein fragrance ``Eternity,'' which Taylor predicted could match the
success of Minnetonka's ``Obsession'' fragrance. Both sell for
around $185 an ounce.
   Sales figures for ``Obsession'' and ``Eternity'' are not
available, said Elin Schomaker, a spokeswoman for the company.
   Taylor said the announcement that Minnetonka is considering the
possibility of a sale does not guarantee ``that this exploration
will result in proposals acceptable to the company or that any
transaction will be consummated.''
   ``We believe there is a significant gap between (Minnetonka's)
current share price level and the value that could be achieved in
the private market,'' Taylor said.
