<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     03-03 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held against most major currencies
today, though some traders believed its recent rally was running out
of steam.
   Gold prices rose.
   One trader in Milan said the dollar's room for upward movement is
limited by the continued worries about the health of the U.S.
economy.
   ``There are still too many fundamentals that are weak in the
U.S.,'' the trader said. Nonetheless, ``I'm not going to be selling
dollars soon.''
   Another trader in Milan said that if the U.S. Senate rejects
President Bush's choice of John Tower as secretary of defense, the
dollar would likely lose ground.
   ``The market generally likes a strong American president. But if
Tower's candidacy fails, the `wimp factor' will re-emerge,'' the
trader said.
   The pound sank in London to $1.7205 from $1.7270 late Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.05 Japanese yen to a closing 128.12 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 128.00 yen.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.8443 West German marks, up from 1.8405; 1.5775
Swiss francs, up from 1.5710; 6.2740 French francs, up from 6.2575;
2.0831 Dutch guilders, up from 2.0735; 1,357.50 Italian lire, down
from 1,360.50; 1.1935 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1945.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $384.30 a troy ounce, up
from $383.75 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $386.50.
   In Zurich, gold was trading at $386.50 at noon, compared with
$383.25 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 86 cents an ounce to close at a
bid $386.75.
   Gold dealers in London said the market appeared to be ignoring
the dollar, while the metal gained strength from some short covering
and buying interest out of Japan and Switzerland.
   Silver bullion rose in London to a bid price of $5.80 a troy
ounce, up from $5.76 late Thursday.
</TEXT>
