<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     03-03 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Steady Against Yen, Shares Off Earlier Highs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar held its ground against the Japanese
yen at the end of trading today, while share prices toppled sharply
from earlier highs to finish the week marginally lower.
   The U.S. dollar finished at 128.12 yen, up only 0.05 yen from
Thursday's 128.07 close. It had started trading at 128.58 yen and
moved mainly between 128.10-128.70 yen during the day.
   Dealers said the dollar was mainly supported by a West German
decision Thursday not to change its interest rates.
   Bundesbank, the West German central bank, said it would maintain
its discount rate and its Lombard interest rate at 4.0 percent and
6.0 percent, respectively.
   ``Because of the announcement, the dollar managed to touch 128.70
yen during the morning session, but fell back in afternoon
trading,'' said a dealer with a major Japanese securities firm.
   He said a speech by Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita in the
afternoon erased gains made by the U.S. currency, causing it to drop
to 128.12 yen.
   In the speech to businessmen, Sumita said the domestic price
situation is becoming ``more severe'' when compared to last year,
and that it was important to act ``promptly and flexibly'' to deter
inflationary fear.
   ``Market participants took that to mean Japan may hike its own
interest rates,'' the dealer said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Japan's discount rate presently stands at 2.5 percent, the lowest
among major industrialized countries.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei index also fell from
earlier gains to close the week marginally lower at 32,000.10
points, down 73.63 points, or 0.22 percent.
   It had started trading with a strong 226.34-point gain, but lost
steam because of profit-taking by cautious investors.
</TEXT>
