<FIRST>r f PM-EmployeeBenefits Bjt   03-03 0701</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Employee Benefits, Bjt,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>IRS Softening Health Plan Anti-Discrimination Rule</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRS is temporarily softening the sting of a
new law affecting the group health insurance of many American
workers, but opponents say the only solution is repeal.
   A bill to kill the law, which requires businesses to demonstrate
that their health plans do not discriminate in favor of upper-income
employees, has been signed by 183 members of the House.
   Rep. John LaFalce, D-N.Y., chairman of the House Small Business
Committee, says he expects a majority of the House _ 218 members _
to have signed his repeal bill within a few weeks.
   One employee-benefits consultant estimates that almost half the
nation's companies with more than 1,000 workers cannot say with
certainty that their plans do not discriminate.
   The Internal Revenue Service on Thursday issued 220 pages of
regulations explaining to employers how they could comply with the
law, which is known as Section 89. The law was enacted as part of
the big tax overhaul of 1986 and amended as recently as last
November.
   Although the law took effect Jan. 1, the IRS said employers need
take no action to comply with it before July 1. In addition, a
good-faith effort to comply will be treated by the IRS as having
satisfied the law at least until next Jan. 1.
   Business representatives said the regulations do nothing to make
th law more attractive.
   ``Section 89 represents a major attack on our employee benefit
system,'' said Karen Berg, human-resources manager for the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce. ``In reality, it's a back-door effort to tax
employee benefits. The length and complexity of the regulations make
it clear that Section 89 should be repealed.''
   ``It is obvious that they have failed to provide understandable
guidance for Section 89,'' said John Sloan Jr., president of the
National Federation of Independent Business.
   Congress enacted Section 89 in an effort to extend health
insurance to more workers. The provision requires employers to apply
complex mathematical tests to their benefits packages to prove that
they are not biased against workers making less than $50,000 a year.
   Many businesses complain that the law, by weighting them down
with paperwork, could have the opposite effect by encouraging
abandonment of employee health insurance.
   Treasury and IRS officials say their discussions with accountants
indicate most businesses will have no major problem complying with
the law. In large part, that assumption reflects that the general
principles applying to health and welfare benefits are similar to
those that have governed employee pensions since 1974.
   The regulations announced Thursday, on which the IRS will take
comments until May 8, apply chiefly to health insurance, since that
is the benefit affecting most employers. However, the transition
rules, including the date changes, also apply to term life insurance.
   Under the law, before an employer's benefit plan can be
considered qualified by the IRS, it must be written, enforceable,
permanent and maintained exclusively for the benefit of workers. If
a plan is not qualified, all employees pay tax on the benefit.
   A second set of requirements is designed to prevent the plan from
being overly beneficial to higher-income workers. If an employer's
plan fails this test, only the highly paid employees _ not
rank-and-file workers _ would have to pay tax on the value of the
excess insurance coverage.
   In explaining the regulations, the IRS scoffed at a story
repeated often by opponents of Section 89. This story holds that a
hypothetical $20,000-a-year janitor whose $150,000 heart surgery is
covered by insurance would have to pay tax on the full $150,000 if
his employer's health plan failed to meet qualification rules.
   ``That result is not reached under these regulations,'' said
James J. McGovern, IRS assistant chief counsel.
   The regulations state that if a plan does not qualify, a worker
making under $50,001 would be liable for tax on only 10 percent of
medical expenses that were reimbursed under the insurance plan. The
percentage would rise with income; a worker earning over $150,000
would pay tax on the full reimbursement.
   The IRS said no penalty would be imposed for a small violation
that was corrected within 90 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
