<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2245EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CBOTChanges     03-03 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CBOT Changes,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBOT Seeks Greater Accountability After Targeting by Federal Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade, whose trading is under
federal investigation, Friday announced measures to provide greater
accountability and a better audit trail of floor trades.
   The Board of Trade's board of directors unanimously approved
implementation of nine ``enhancements'' of the exchange's
surveillance system, said spokeswoman Jane Crowley.
   The measures were approved after disclosure last month of a
2-year undercover federal probe into suspected illegal trading
practices at the BOT and the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. No
indictments have yet been announced as a result of the ongoing
investigation, in which FBI agents have posed as traders to look
into allegations of pre-arranged trades and other illegal practices.
   ``The timing, obviously, has some ties to the investigation,''
said a Board of Trade official who asked not to be identified. ``But
they (Board of Trade directors) have been making changes to improve
the system since it went in three years ago.''
   Crowley said most of the measures involve changes in the
time-reporting system.
   Traders record trades within 30-minute windows on cards that are
collected at 10:30 a.m. CST and again at the close of business in
each trading pit.
   The new measures would double the number of windows, make them
15-minute sessions, and require collection of traders' cards hourly.
   Finally, the clocks of all brokerage houses operating at the
exchange would be sychronized with the Board of Trade's floor clock,
ensuring greater uniformity in time-stamping trades.
   In another development, both the Board of Trade and the Merc have
asked member traders not to respond to a Wall Street Journal survey
requesting opinions on the federal probe.
   Merc officials sent out a five-page letter urging members to
beware of the ``deviously phrased'' survey. The letter also cites
``defects'' in 10 of the survey's 12 questions that Merc officials
said are calculated to produce a ``distorted story.''
   Board of Trade officials, meanwhile, told members that any survey
responses ``may undermine our efforts to reinforce investor
confidence in the integrity of our markets.''
   The survey asked traders for their opinions on FBI tactics, on
whether there was cheating at the exchanges and to what extent, and
the effectiveness of internal disciplinary actions.
   A spokesman for Dow Jones &amp; Co., publisher of the Journal called
the survey a ``standard reporting technique.''
</TEXT>
