<FIRST>r f AM-ChryslerOdometers     03-03 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler Odometers,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Slow To Pay Settlement In Odometer Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s delay in mailing settlement
checks in a disconnected odometer case has cost the automaker loyal
customers, some consumers said.
   The automaker negotiated the settlement with officials in 45
states more than 14 months ago. The agreement came after a federal
grand jury charged two company employees with conspiring to sell
more than 60,000 vehicles whose odometers were disconnected while
they were driven by Chrysler officials.
   Consumers who bought the vehicles were supposed to receive $500
each, but the checks never went in the mail.
   ``If they had sent me the $500 I probably would have gone right
out and bought another Chrysler,'' Doris Smith of Grosse Pointe
said. ``But my husband went out and bought a Sterling and it runs
like a dream. They lost a longtime customer.''
   Many consumers say they haven't even received a claim form that
they were told last August would be mailed to them shortly
thereafter, the Detroit Free Press said Friday.
   ```Shortly thereafter' in court terms can mean anywhere from one
to two years,'' said Marcia Darling-Aud, a court employee at U.S.
District Court in St. Louis.
   The biggest problem at the moment is identifying all those
entitled to receive the settlement checks, Darling-Aud said.
   She added the money is sitting in a St. Louis bank collecting
interest. That means the eventual settlement may be more than $500,
Chrysler spokeswoman Karen Stewart said.
</TEXT>
