<FIRST>r f AM-PeoplesDrug     03-03 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peoples Drug,0200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imasco Sells More Peoples Drug Outlets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Imasco Ltd. said Friday it has agreed to sell
114 stores in its Peoples Drug Store chain, mostly in Ohio, to Rite
Aid Corp.
   No financial details of the transaction were disclosed.
   Peoples, which is based in Alexandria, Va., operates 745 stores
in 11 states and the District of Columbia. The company is a wholly
owned subsidiary of Imasco, which is headquartered in Montreal.
   Imasco announced in January that it would sell about 240 Peoples
stores in Indiana and Ohio. It has also announced the sale of 80
stores in Peoples' Atlanta division.
   Rite Aid, located in Harrisburg, Pa., operates 2,200 stores,
mainly in the East.
   The latest deal, which is subject to regulatory approval, is
expected to close in mid-April, according to a statement from Imasco
Limited, the parent company of Peoples Drug.
   Once the sales are completed, Peoples will have about 500 stores
in the Washington, D.C., area, the mid-Atlantic region and
Pennsylvania.
   Imasco is a major Canadian consumer products and services
company, whose operations include Hardee's fast food restaurants,
Shoppers Drug Mart, and Imperial Tobacco.
