<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   03-03 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures End Mostly Lower; Corn Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat, oats and soybean futures prices closed
lower Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade but corn finished mixed
in response to a lower-than-expected forecast for Argentine corn
production.
   In a day of subdued trading, most of the selling was attributed
to pre-weekend profit-taking after Thursday's steep rally in the
soybean market, which raised prices to a 4-week high.
   Crop futures also were pressured by reports of widespread
precipitation in the Midwest and the Plains, and by forecasts for
more snow and rain during the weekend.
   The precipitation will help recharge soil parched by last
summer's drought and provide protective snow cover for some of the
winter wheat crop.
   Support for the corn market stemmed from the Argentine National
Grain Board's estimate Thursday of a 4.77 million-metric-ton corn
harvest this spring.
   The estimate compares with last year's harvest of 8.88 million
metric tons. The crop suffered heavy drought damage, effectively
eliminating Argentina as a major corn exporter during the 1989-90
crop year.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 3} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.32{ a bushel; corn was 1 cent
lower to 2} cents higher with March at $2.78\ a bushel; oats were 2
cents to 4{ cents lower with March at $2.05{ a bushel; soybeans were
{ cent to 7\ cents lower with March at $7.67 a bushel.
</TEXT>
