<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Mood     03-03 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Mood,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mood is Anxious at Eastern Terminals, in Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Stands for MIAMI-dated Aboard Eastern on AM Business News Digest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The anxiety of passengers and Eastern Airlines
employees was evident Friday at Eastern terminals and in the air as
the midnight deadline loomed for a strike against the ailing carrier.
   Operations seemed to be running normally at Eastern's terminal at
LaGuardia Airport in New York and there was no evidence of
additional police presence Friday morning.
   But bitter employees were vocal about Eastern management and
pessimistic about the prospects for a last-minute settlement of the
dispute between Eastern and its Machinists union.
   ``There's tremendous anger'' at Frank Lorenzo, the chairman of
Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., said a male flight attendant
onboard an early morning run from New York to Miami.
   ``I would rather see the airline burn to the ground'' than have
it continue under current management, said the employee from Queens,
N.Y., who has worked for Eastern for 11 years.
   The New York-Miami flight, which had been overbooked, was delayed
nearly an hour while flight attendants offered free round-trip
tickets on Eastern to passengers willing to give up their seats.
There were few takers, but precious minutes went by as the gamblers
left the aircraft and seats were found for the passengers replacing
them.
   At the terminal, Florida-bound passengers worried about getting
back to New York quizzed ticket agents _ some of whom, at least,
seemed to be making an extra effort to be courteous and upbeat. The
check-in lines were fairly long but orderly and fast-moving.
   Lorenzo ``is in a class by himself,'' said one agent, who
reported she had been besieged by questions from passengers. She
expressed optimism, though, that an 11th-hour settlement could be
reached to avert a strike, as happened in 1986 when former Eastern
chairman Frank Borman sold the airline to Lorenzo.
   Some passengers joked about the hardship of not being able to get
back to New York when temperatures in Florida were running at around
80 degrees.
   But others were anxious.
   A young woman on the New York-Miami flight, due to take another
Eastern flight from Miami to San Juan, Puerto Rico, on Saturday was
worried that she and the 190-member tour group she was escorting
wouldn't make it.
   ``If the pilots go on strike (with the Eastern Machinists), this
airline is finished,'' she said. ``I'd hate to see another American
company go under; I would rather see their prices go up than a
company go under.''
   An Eastern pilot riding ``jump seat'' on the flight _ not working
but transiting to his next assignment _ insisted that a Machinists'
strike against Eastern can't be effective without the support of the
pilots. The pilots union at Eastern has balloted its members, but
the results haven't yet been announced.
   ``I don't think (Eastern management) has run the airline very
well,'' the 10-year pilot said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
