<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2334EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-LauraAshley-Limited     03-03 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Laura Ashley-Limited,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Laura Ashley Says U.S. Retailer Copying Its Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laura Ashley Holdings PLC Friday charged U.S.
retailer Limited Inc. with copying the bottles and packaging design
of perfumes sold by a Laura Ashley subsidiary.
   A suit filed in federal court in New York by Laura Ashley and its
Penhaligon's Ltd. subsidiary seeks to stop Victoria's Secret shops
owned by Limited from selling perfumes in bottles and packaging
designs that allegedly are direct copies of ones used by
Penhaligon's.
   The complaint says Limited and Victoria's Secret produced the
knock-off line after they were unsuccessful in their attempts to
acquire Penhaligon's.
   Besides seeking to stop the manufacture and sale of the perfumes,
Laura Ashley is seeking an unspecified amount in monetary damages.
   A statement from Laura Ashley, which is a British company that
sells women's fashions, fabrics and some home furnishings, said the
suit was filed as a claim of unfair competition under the U.S.
trademark law and New York state law. Laura Ashley has been
expanding its U.S. presence in recent years.
   Penhaligon's, also based in Britain, has been in business since
the 1870s as a perfume retailer and was acquired by Laura Ashley in
1987.
   Its fragrance products are sold in about a dozen U.S. department
stores and to over 2,500 mail order customers. The statement said
Leslie H. Wexner, Limited's chairman, is one of the mail order
customers.
   Penhaligon's perfumes come in glass-stoppered bottles with an
unusual shape. The company has been awarded Royal Warrants from the
Duke of Edinburgh and the Prince of Wales and its perfume packaging
bears seals to reflect the endorsements.
   The suit claims Limited and Victoria's Secret have tried to
simulate the Royal Warrant on their perfume packaging.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
