<DOCNO> AP890303-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-AutoSales     03-03 0569</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Auto Sales,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Car and Truck Sales Plummet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales by the nation's Big Three
automakers continued their 1989 skid in late February, falling 17.9
percent compared with the same period last year, the automakers
reported Friday.
   Chrysler Corp.'s car sales for late February were 30.7 percent
behind last year. General Motors Corp.'s were off 25.4 percent. Car
sales for Ford Motor Co. rose 0.4 percent during the Feb. 11-28
period.
   Truck sales by the Big Three fell 15.5 percent compared to the
same period last year, while car sales fell 19.3 percent.
   U.S.-made cars sold by GM, Ford and Chrysler sold at an average
daily rate of 26,062 during the period this year. That compares with
an average of 32,297 cars sold daily during the same period last
year.
   There were seven selling days during late February this year and
last year.
   Sales of light trucks made by the Big Three averaged 15,561 a day
in late February this year, compared with a daily rate of 18,419
during the same time last year.
   Combined, cars and trucks sold at a rate of 41,624 a day during
the period this year, compared with 50,716 in late February last
year.
   During January and February of last year, car and truck sales
were above average as strong incentives continued to draw buyers
into showrooms. Incentives are continuing but on a narrower range of
vehicles.
   For the year through February, the Big Three's car sales have
slipped 10.6 percent to a daily rate of 19,717 from a rate of 22,047
for the first two months of last year. Light truck sales dropped 1.9
percent during January and February of this year to a daily rate of
12,166 from a rate of 12,404 last year.
   There were 50 selling days during the first two months of this
year, one more than last year.
   Chrysler's car sales dropped a whopping 30.7 percent during late
February, falling to an average daily rate of 3,710 this year
compared with a rate of 5,354 last year. For the first two months of
the year, Chrysler has sold cars at a pace 18.4 percent below that
of 1988.
   On the truck side, Chrysler fared a little better, with late
February sales 1.3 percent below last year's rate. Truck sales for
the year to date by Chrysler are running 5.7 percent above last
year's pace.
   GM, the nation's largest automaker, said its car sales fell 25.4
percent in late February, dropping to a rate of 13,598 this year
from 18,221 last year. During the first two months of the year, GM's
car sales have slipped 14.6 percent.
   GM's truck sales, meanwhile, fell 29.2 percent during the period
this year compared with the same time last year. Through February,
sales of GM trucks are running 7.7 percent below last year's pace.
   Ford reported a 0.4 percent rise in car sales during late
February, going to a daily rate of 8,755 from 8,721 during the same
period last year. Through February of this year, Ford's car sales
have risen 0.5 percent.
   Truck sales for Ford in late February fell 5.3 percent compared
with the same period last year. Truck sales through February of this
year are 0.1 percent higher than they were during the first two
months of last year.
</TEXT>
