<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1655EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     03-03 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures prices declined in volatile
trading Friday, with crude oil soaring toward the $19-a-barrel level
before settling lower in a wave of technical selling.
   Refined petroleum products also lost ground.
   ``It was a volatile day,'' said Peter Beutel, an energy analyst
with Elders Futures Inc.
   Beutel said prices started out weak following reports that
production among the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
had been higher than expected during January and February.
   But he said the market started to rally later in the session
after non-OPEC nations Mexico, Egypt and the Soviet Union announced
5 percent cuts in their oil output.
   Several non-OPEC nations had agreed at a London conference last
month to cut oil production in coordination with an earlier
production pact between cartel members.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the April contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 16 cents lower
at $18.56 a barrel, after rising as high as $18.88 a barrel at one
point during Friday's session.
   Traders said prices declined in a wave of technical selling after
the WTI April contract failed to pierce the psychologically
important $19-a-barrel level.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
April contract for wholesale home heating oil settled 1.07 cents
lower at 50.80 cents a gallon. April unleaded gasoline settled at
51.53 cents, down 0.68 cent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
