<DOCNO> AP890303-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 2345EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-PrimeComputer     03-03 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prime Computer,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>MAI Basic Four Launches Proxy Fight For Prime Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intensifying the battle to take over Prime Computer
Inc., MAI Basic Four Inc. said Friday it will wage a proxy fight for
control of Prime's board of directors at the May 12 annual meeting.
   MAI Basic announced a slate of nominees for the election, which
will fill all seven seats on the board by a majority vote of the
stockholders represented at the meeting.
   Prime spokesman Joseph Gavaghan said the announcement was ``not
unanticipated'' and that Prime will urge shareholders to retain the
current board.
   MAI Basic, a computer firm based in Tustin, Calif., launched a
$20-per-share hostile bid for Prime in mid-November. The offer is
valued at $970 million.
   In a prepared statement, MAI Basic said its slate of directors
would be committed to selling Prime, a manufacturer of minicomputers
and computer-aided design and manufacturing systems.
   Prime, which has headquarters in Natick, Mass., issued a response
saying MAI Basic's bid ``continues to be highly conditional,
unfinanced and extremely leveraged'' and that ``the price does not
reflect the intrinsic value of Prime.''
   MAI Basic's takeover offer has been enjoined since Dec. 9, when a
U.S. District Court judge in Boston ruled that MAI Basic had not
disclosed sufficient information about its financing arrangements
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   MAI Basic has appealed the injunction to the U.S. Court of
Appeals.
   Bennett S. LeBow, chairman of MAI Basic, said in a prepared
statement that it ``would seriously consider raising its
$20-per-share, all-cash offer for all outstanding shares of Prime in
the context of a negotiated transaction in which (MAI Basic Four) is
provided information by Prime that demonstrates that such an
increase is warranted.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
