<FIRST>u f AM-Boeing-Lockheed     03-03 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boeing-Lockheed,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lockheed Stock Rises On Takeover Speculation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. stock jumped Friday after Business
Week reported rival aerospace giant Boeing Co. may try to buy the
company.
   The ``Inside Wall Street'' stock-tipping column in March 13
editions of the business newsweekly, published late Thursday and
available on newsstands next week, quoted unidentified sources as
saying Boeing is keenly interested in Lockheed's enormous defense
contracting business.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, Lockheed rose $1.75 a share to
$49.50 in consolidated trading. Boeing rose $1.62{ to $65.12{.
   The column quoted an unidentified money manager as saying Boeing
can easily afford to buy Lockheed because it has $4.2 billion in
cash with little debt. Lockheed's market value at its current price
is about $3 billion, although a purchaser would likely have to pay
more to acquire the shares.
   The column also said Boeing's own military sales aren't expected
to grow this year, whereas Lockheed's have grown 30 percent annually
since 1982.
   Both companies declined to comment on takeover speculation.
   Lockheed, based in Calabasas, Calif., is a leader in research,
development and production of aerospace and defense products.
   Seattle-based Boeing also is deeply involved in defense-related
projects and is the undisputed leader in the commercial jetliner
industry.
   Lockheed ranked eighth in defense contracts in fiscal 1988, with
$3.54 billion, while Boeing ranked 10th with $3 billion, the
Pentagon said this week.
   Lockheed's stock also jumped late last year when Texas investor
Harold Simmons, through his majority-owned Valhi Inc., sought
clearance from the Federal Trade Commission to buy up to 15 percent
of Lockheed. Valhi so far has acquired less than 1 percent of the
stock.
</TEXT>
