<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0039EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SEC-Auditors     03-03 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SEC-Auditors,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rule Change Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission approved
rule changes Thursday designed to give investors faster notice when
corporate auditors turn up fraud or other irregularities.
   Under the previous rules, a company had up to 15 days to report
the resignation of its auditor in a dispute and an additional 30
days after that to make public a letter from the auditor outlining
the disagreement.
   The new rule, approved on a 4-0 vote, requires companies to
report the resignation of an auditor within five days and to file
the auditor's letter with the SEC within 10 days, thus tightening up
the disclosure period from 45 days to 15 days.
   The changes come more than a year after members of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee complained about the rule during a
January 1988 hearing on the notorious ZZZZ Best fraud case.
   Barry Minkow, a teenage California financial wizard, parlayed a
rug-cleaning business based in his parents' garage into a
multimillion-dollar, publicly traded corporation.
   ZZZZ Best's independent auditor, Ernst &amp; Whinney, discovered
irregularities and resigned on June 2, 1986. But, the firm's
suspicions weren't made public until July 16, 1986. In the meantime,
unwitting investors continued to buy ZZZZ Best stock, which became
worthless.
   Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., had been pressing for even faster
disclosure of irregularities turned up by accountants, by requiring
the accountants to go directly to the SEC with their suspicions.
   But, SEC Chairman David S. Ruder told Wyden at a hearing last
year the commission lacked the power to require reports directly
from auditors. Ruder said he would support a change in the law
giving the commission that power.
   The commission plans to publish its new rules within several
weeks. They would become effective 30 days after that.
   SEC member Edward Fleischman expressed concern that the tightened
deadline would create a burden on firms, but the SEC staff said
there had been only about a half dozen cases within the past six
months that would have been affected.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890303-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 0048EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Globex-MATIF     03-03 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Globex-MATIF,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merc Signs French Futures Exchange to Globex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The French futures exchange Marche a Terme
International de France has agreed to join Globex, an off-hours
electronic trading system being developed by the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange and Reuters Holdings PLC, officials said Thursday.
   The French exchange, which is known by its acronym MATIF, is the
third outside exchange to announce its intention to join Globex and
offer products for trading on the system.
   The New York Mercantile Exchange, which trades primarily oil and
platinum futures, and the Sydney Futures Exchange of Australia
previously announced plans to join Globex.
   The MATIF is Europe's highest-volume futures exchange and the
first in the European time zones to join Globex. It lists a variety
of financial and commodity futures including a French government
bond futures contract and a stock-index futures contract based on 40
stocks traded on the Paris Bourse stock exchange.
   Leo Melamed, chairman of the Chicago Merc's executive committee,
said the addition of the French exchange to Globex would give the
system a partner in each of the world's three major time zones,
making Globex ``the worldwide transaction system it set out to
become.''
   The automated system, which is expected to become operational
this fall, will use a computer to match buy and sell orders during
the hours that the member exchanges' trading floors are closed.
   The Chicago Merc, the world's second-largest futures exchange,
and London-based Reuters announced plans to create the system in
1987.
   Futures are contracts to buy or sell a commodity or financial
instrument at an agreed-upon price at a specified future date.
   The Chicago Board of Trade, the world's largest futures exchange,
announced last month that it was developing its own automated
off-hours trading system to compete with Globex.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
