<FILEID>AP-NR-03-03-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     03-03 0688</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supply Fears Fuel 5-Day Copper Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Persistent supply concerns pushed copper futures prices sharply
higher Friday on New York's Commodity Exchange, capping a weeklong
rally that boosted copper by more than 10 percent.
   On other exchanges, precious metals also advanced; energy futures
retreated; pork bellies plummeted, leading livestock futures lower;
and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Copper settled 2.4 cents to 5.6 cents higher with the most active
contract, for delivery in May, at $1.437 a pound. The spot March
contract finished at $1.53 a pound compared with the spot settlement
price of $1.386 a pound a week earlier.
   Prices rose despite an apparent reduction in tensions between
Peruvian copper miners and the government.
   In Peru, the world's sixth-largest copper-producing nation, the
National Federation of Mine Workers continued plans for a 3-day
``warning strike'' beginning March 26. The miners contend the
government has not honored the agreement that ended a 57-day strike
late last year.
   The union said Friday it was willing to accept some compromises
in the interim before the strike, although workers did not rule out
possibly extending the strike beyond three days.
   Copper's underlying supply-and-demand factors remained
overwhelmingly bullish, with near-term availability extremely
limited going into the second quarter, historically a period of
heavy consumption.
   ``We have a convergence of the technical, fundamental and
seasonal factors,'' said William O'Neill, research director with
Elders Futures Inc. in New York. ``This is an extremely positive
period for the market.''
   The Commodity Exchange reported that copper supplies deliverable
against the March contract increased by 113 tons Thursday to 17,446
tons. But analysts said copper stocks are so low that the increase
had scant market impact.
   Precious-metals futures prices rose amid fears that a strike in
the industrial-metals section of South Africa's Rustenburg mining
complex could spread to the platinum sector. Rustenburg is the
world's largest platinum mine.
   A drop in the dollar's value against other major currencies also
contributed to the rise in precious metal values, analysts said.
   Platinum settled $5.40 to $5.60 higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange with April at $539.30 a troy ounce. On the Commodity
Exchange, gold settled $2.70 to $3.20 higher with April at $389.30 a
troy ounce; silver was 3.9 cents to 4.8 cents higher with March at
$5.801 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures traded higher for most of the session on the New
York Merc but finished lower after a late wave of profit-taking that
erased nearly half of the previous day's strong gains in the crude
oil market.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 16 cents to 22 cents
lower with April at $18.56 a barrel; heating oil was .59 cent to
1.07 cents lower with April at 50.80 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .36 cent to .72 cent lower with April at 51.53 cents a
gallon.
   Heavy profit-taking in the pork belly market led the decline in
livestock and meat futures prices on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange. The March belly contract plummeted 2 cents a pound, the
maximum daily price change permitted by the exchange.
   Live cattle settled .20 cent to .55 cent lower with April at
77.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .45 cent lower
with March at 82.42 cents a pound; live hogs were .40 cent lower to
.08 cent higher with April at 44.15 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were 2 cents lower to .48 cent higher with March at 37.25
cents a pound.
   Wheat, oats and soybean futures prices settled mostly lower on
the Chicago Board of Trade but corn finished mixed in response to a
lower-than-expected forecast for Argentine corn production.
   Most of the selling was triggered by profit-taking the soybean
market, which soared to a 4-week high on Thursday.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3{ cents lower with March at $4.32} a
bushel; corn was 1 cent lower to 2} cents higher with March at
$2.78\ a bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with March at
$2.05{ a bushel; soybeans were 8 cents lower to { cent higher with
March at $7.67} a bushel.
</TEXT>
