<FIRST>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   03-03 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Car And Truck Sales Slip 10.5 Percent In February</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales in the United States slipped
10.5 percent during February, led downward by a 30.7 percent decline
in Chrysler Corp. car sales during the last week of the month,
automakers reported Friday.
   Sales of U.S. and imported cars and light trucks showed declines
for late February, for the entire month and for the first two months
of this year compared with the corresponding periods of 1988.
   During the Feb. 21-28 period, car and truck sales reported by the
eight domestic vehicle producers were down 14.3 percent this year
compared with the same time last year. Vehicles sold at an average
daily rate of 46,336 during the period this year, compared with a
daily rate of 54,044 vehicles during late February last year.
   Industry insiders have predicted that 1989 sales will be softer
than in 1988, the second-best calendar sales year on record. Part of
the reason for the good year last year were strong sales during
January and February due to heavy use of incentives.
   Incentives have been in effect this year, but on a smaller number
of cars and light trucks.
   The sales slides in late February and for the month surprised
analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. of New York City.
   ``They came in lower than I expected,'' he said, adding that some
incentives for General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. ended during
the last part of the month. ``It's leaving the industry with a lot
of inventory.''
   Healy estimated that GM had 85 days' worth, Ford 88 and Chrysler
84.
   On Friday, GM announced it was extending for two more weeks a
shutdown of its Doraville, Ga., assembly plant, which makes
Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme cars. GM blamed the extended shutdown,
which affected 4,000 workers, on high inventories.
   ``We've got too many cars out in the field,'' said Doraville
plant manager F. Thomas Brady.
   Among the nation's Big Three automakers, Ford alone showed
increased sales during late February, the month or during the first
two months of the year. But those gains were tiny.
   The nation's No. 2 automaker said it sold cars at a daily rate of
8,755 during late February this year, up 0.4 percent from the 8,721
daily rate during the same period last year. For the month, Ford's
car sales slipped 2.3 percent and for the year, the company is
selling cars at a rate 0.5 percent higher than the same time last
year.
   Chrysler's sales of domestic cars skidded 30.7 percent during
late February. Analysts and company officials have said the nation's
No. 3 automaker is suffering a bit from having too little variety in
its product lineup. Chrysler's monthly sales were off 26.8 percent
last month when compared with February a year ago. Car sales during
the first two months at Chrysler are at a pace 18.4 percent below
last year's during the same time.
   GM's domestic car sales also fell dramatically compared with last
year, dropping 25.4 percent in late February, 17.1 percent for the
entire month and 14.6 percent for the first two months of the year.
</TEXT>
